     to what you're looking for, then fill our the template below. Please read
     our guide to filing a bug first: https://flutter.dev/docs/resources/bug-reports
-->
On web the top and left borders of an `OutlineButton` disappear and reappears as the window is resized. 

Currently experiencing on this on dev 1.14.3. I tried to run it on master, but ran into this problem:  https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/49103#issuecomment-577005820

## Steps to Reproduce

[Minimal sample repo](https://github.com/buntagonalprism/outline_button_edge_issue)
main.dart from the sample repo - just add an Outline button to the starter project:
```
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';

void main() => runApp(MyApp());

class MyApp extends StatelessWidget {
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return MaterialApp(
      title: 'Flutter Demo',
      theme: ThemeData(
        primarySwatch: Colors.blue,
      ),
      home: MyHomePage(),
    );
  }
}

class MyHomePage extends StatefulWidget {
  @override
  _MyHomePageState createState() => _MyHomePageState();
}

class _MyHomePageState extends State<MyHomePage> {
  int _counter = 0;

  void _incrementCounter() {
    setState(() => _counter++);
  }

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Scaffold(
      appBar: AppBar(
        title: Text('Outline Button Edge Issue'),
      ),
      body: Center(
        child: Column(
          mainAxisAlignment: MainAxisAlignment.center,
          children: <Widget>[
            Text('You have pushed the button this many times:'),
            Text(
              '$_counter',
              style: Theme.of(context).textTheme.display1,
            ),
            OutlineButton(
              child: Text('Increment'),
              onPressed: _incrementCounter,
            ),
          ],
        ),
      ),
    );
  }
}
```

**Expected results:** <!-- what did you want to see? -->
All borders present around outline button
![working-resolution](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/12552169/72885242-9dfad080-3d5b-11ea-820e-9f1965da8703.JPG)

**Actual results:** <!-- what did you see? -->
Left edge of border missing at some resolutions
![broken-resolution](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/12552169/72885258-a81ccf00-3d5b-11ea-86e0-ccac9939b44d.JPG)

Title_Description:
WillPopScope assumes immediate disposal on route change On the `master` channel, I'm getting the error when navigating away from a page with a `Form` (and thus a `WillPopScope`) with `Navigator.maybePop(context)`, when the `Form` is not unmounted before route disposal: ``` 'package:flutter/src/widgets/will_pop_scope.dart': Failed assertion: line 59 pos 12: '_route == ModalRoute.of(context)': is not true. Either the assertion indicates an error in the framework itself, or we should provide substantially more information in this error message to help you determine and fix the underlying cause. In either case, please report this assertion by filing a bug on GitHub: https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/new?template=BUG.md The relevant error-causing widget was Form-[LabeledGlobalKey#4274e] lib/task/edit_task_page.dart:92 When the exception was thrown, this was the stack #2 _WillPopScopeState.didUpdateWidget package:flutter/閳/widgets/will_pop_scope.dart:59 #3 StatefulElement.update package:flutter/閳/widgets/framework.dart:4571 #4 Element.updateChild package:flutter/閳/widgets/framework.dart:3141 #5 ComponentElement.performRebuild package:flutter/閳/widgets/framework.dart:4412 #6 Element.rebuild package:flutter/閳/widgets/framework.dart:4116 ... ``` I believe this is because I am not using the typical flutter navigation animations and am instead using in-place animations along with a non-animating custom route: ```dart class NoAnimationMaterialPageRoute extends MaterialPageRoute { NoAnimationMaterialPageRoute({ @required WidgetBuilder builder, RouteSettings settings, bool maintainState = true, bool fullscreenDialog = false, }) : super( builder: builder, maintainState: maintainState, settings: settings, fullscreenDialog: fullscreenDialog, ); @override Widget buildTransitions( BuildContext context, Animation animation, Animation secondaryAnimation, Widget child, ) { return child; } @override Duration get transitionDuration => const Duration(milliseconds: 0); } ``` This is admittedly a bit of a niche/hackish use-case, but I think it would also apply to a form nested in a `Hero`

Title_Description:
Stabilize Linux embedding/runner boundary There is preliminary support for `flutter create` for Linux, but it's explicitly unstable. We need to make firm decisions on the embedding API and the build system/tool interaction so that we can declare it stable (meaning we expect that the output of `flutter create` will continue working with future versions of Flutter, rather than need to be recreated frequently) and remove the warnings and checks related to the current instability.

Blockers (this will be a living list):
- [x] #30729
- [x] #52744
- [x] #52751

Creator: stuartmorgan

Title_Description:
Document packaging for Windows builds See https://github.com/google/flutter-desktop-embedding/issues/587 for earlier discussion.

We should very likely either:
- switch the templates for apps and plugins to use the static runtime, or
- update the app bundling script to copy in the runtime libraries into the output directory for ease of packaging.

From my initial investigation in the original bug:
> I did a quick experiment, and using the static runtime increases the size of each of the current FDE plugins from ~50-70K to ~300-500K, and Testbed.exe from ~100K to ~500K.
>
> While that's not all that much in current desktop machine size terms, it's not clear to me that the benefit of doing that vs. having a simple path to bundling the necessary runtime libraries (e.g., adding to bundle_assets_and_deps) is the right approach. We should look more into the tradeoffs in terms of potential interactions between plugins, which would be more isolated with a static runtime.
Labels: tool;platform-windows;a: desktop;documentation;a: build;P4
Creator: stuartmorgan

Title_Description:
Shows blinking effect and moves FAB on iOS when switching back from other apps while soft keyboard is open 
When an external application returns to the flutter application while the ios soft keyboard  is turned on, the app will appear a short white splash screen, and the height of the splash screen is the height of the ios soft keyboard. This phenomenon appeared when I tested many flutter apps.

## Steps to Reproduce

1. Run my flutter app in my iphone Successful.
2. Open a  external application which can open  Apple's  soft keyboard  
3. Bring up the keybord
4.back my flutter app 
 


## Actual results 
It will appear white screen. and white screen's height is same as the soft keyboard .
This bug will not appear in Android.

Title_Description:
Provide an ability to annotate locale for accessibility ## Use case
Developers should be able to specify the accessibility locale for UI elements, including text, in their apps. This information could then be used by assistive technology software to either switch TTS languages  on the fly or perhaps load different Braille table based on the specified   locale.

If a accessibility layer is not aware that the element is in a different locale, for example, the screen reader may pronounce it using system default locale, which may be different from the one the app is using.

## Proposal

Both iOS and Android provide a way to annotate locale via [accessibilityLanguage](https://developer.apple.com/documentation/objectivec/nsobject/1615192-accessibilitylanguage) and [LocaleSpan](https://developer.android.com/reference/android/text/style/LocaleSpan) respectively.
It would be great for Flutter to provide a similar semantic affordance for developers.
Labels: framework;engine;a: accessibility;a: internationalization;proposal;passed first triage;P4

Title_Description: Why require NSAllowsArbitraryLoads in video_player plugin? I come from an iOS background and I'm a bit confused by this documentation in the video_player plugin: I've only ever used this in development and never in production due to its security risks as per [apples guidelines](https://developer.apple.com/documentation/bundleresources/information_property_list/nsapptransportsecurity/nsallowsarbitraryloads): > Use this key with caution because it significantly reduces the security of your app. So I'm unsure why its required for use of this plugin and with no clear explanation as to why. It is unclear whether this is necessary for ALL links or just http ones but if the latter i think this should be made clearer in the docs as this is a worrying thing to be suggesting people do in production apps in my opinion. I am dubious to begin integrating this in to my app without knowing whether this is a dead set requirement or not! Thanks in advance!

     to what you're looking for, then fill our the template below. Please read
     our guide to filing a bug first: https://flutter.dev/docs/resources/bug-reports
-->

Hi, I'm using **CustomScrollView**/**SliverFillRemaining**  and expecting an iOS-like BouncingScrollPhysics effect.

## Steps to Reproduce

<!-- You must include full steps to reproduce so that we can reproduce the problem. -->

I tried to follow the [demo](https://api.flutter.dev/flutter/widgets/SliverFillRemaining-class.html), which creates a local project using 
```flutter create --sample=widgets.SliverFillRemaining.4 mysample```.

**Expected results:** <!-- what did you want to see? -->

iOS-like Scroll&Stretch Effect.

**Actual results:** <!-- what did you see? -->

I didn't get the expected scroll & stretch effect and the widgets are just unscrollable.

I have tested on Android Virtual Device and a physical device (Android 9.0) with flutter stable version v1.12.13+hotfix.9 and 1.17.0 and got the same results.

Title_Description:
Support --tree-shake-icons for the web Currently --tree-shake-icons is on by default for mobile & desktop and disabled for the web.

### Background

--tree-shake-icons uses the const_finder binary to parse the tree-shaken kernel file  produced by frontend_server/TFA before it is fed to gen_snapshot for release builds. This kernel file should contain const references to all IconData used within an application. By collecting the set of code points and font families, we can thin the set of bundled fonts.

### Problem

Unlike mobile/desktop, web release builds do not use the frontend_server or gen_snapshot, instead the entire process is handled by dart2s, from source to JavaScript. While dart2js supports tree-shaking as well, it never surfaces the tree-shaken kernel from the build process so it can be parsed by const finder. Initially it seemed like we could run with `--cfe-only` on dart2js, but this produces an un-tree-shaken kernel file, meaning it likely contains many more icons than are actually used.

### Solutions

A few possible solutions were discussed, and some we dismissed:

1. Use a frontend_server generated kernel file with TFA applied. 

It's not clear if this would actually work, since the VM and dart2js platforms have different entrypoints, which could lead to different code being retained. A more trivial case would be something like a conditional import which contained different icons in vm/javascript branches. It would also require two almost identical compilations.

2. Add dart2js kernel target to frontend_server

This is a less hacky version of (1). If we use the right kernel target and platform, then in theory we remove some of the obvious cases where tree shaking is wrong. This still leaves the possibility that there are non-trivial edge cases where dart2js tree-shaking and TFA tree-shaking differ. I haven't yet proven to myself this is an issue

3. Teach dart2js to TFA

This seems like it would be a rather intrusive change to the compilers, and not clear that it would actually be better. Any decision to use TFA in dart2js would need to be made by the Dart web compilers team.

4. Teach dart2js to write tree-shaken kernel to file

According to discussion with the Dart web compilers team, this doesn't really exist in dart2js today .

Title_Description:
MacOS Desktop build: Default font of material (SF UI) does not work on Mac OS 10.12 ## Steps to Reproduce

Building a MacOS desktop app with default ThemeData (unchanged TargetPlatform) and running it on MacOS 10.12 seems to produce font problems.

Unfortunately I don't have a chance to test on MacOS 10.12, [but a user report a weird font problem](https://github.com/authpass/authpass/issues/74): 
![82554506-c27e8200-9b6e-11ea-88a7-ff002df81a4a](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/313066/82666738-caa1f480-9c36-11ea-89b3-8d00d5d505db.png)

I have then tried to use Google Fonts to load alternative fonts, and this solved the issue. So it's definitely a problem with the default font of the theme.

Not sure if this is something which has to be fixed in flutter, since desktop is still just a preview and not sure if MacOS 10.12 should be "supported"(?). But I don't quite understand the problem, as the default theme on TargetPlatform.macOS uses SF UI and afaik this should be available since 10.11.

Hello!
I came across this bug recently (1.18, beta channel), and I am sure this is a flutter issue.
I reproduced it on different web browsers, and here, in the interactive example: https://flutter.dev/docs/cookbook/design/tabs

The bug is present in CanvasKit too.

After switching to the next tab, and then back to the one with the checkbox, the bug disappears until I reload the app.

## Steps to Reproduce

<!-- You must include full steps to reproduce so that we can reproduce the problem. -->


1. Create a TabBarView widget.
2. Put a checkbox in one of the tabs.
3. Hover the cursor over the checkbox.

**Expected results:** The checkbox displays its shadow defined by "hoverColor".<!-- what did you want to see? -->

**Actual results:** No visual response (no shadow). It breaks the interactive feel of the widget.<!-- what did you see? -->

Title_Description:
Flutter Web with CanvasKit: TextField with custom font won't display some characters <!-- Thank you for using Flutter!

     If you are looking for support, please check out our documentation
     or consider asking a question on Stack Overflow:
      * https://flutter.dev/
      * https://api.flutter.dev/
      * https://stackoverflow.com/questions/tagged/flutter?sort=frequent

     If you have found a bug or if our documentation doesn't have an answer
     to what you're looking for, then fill our the template below. Please read
     our guide to filing a bug first: https://flutter.dev/docs/resources/bug-reports
-->

There are multiple issues related to incorrect characters rendering in CanvasKit. 
I suppose this is a slightly different case because it is related to a custom font from `google_fonts`.

If I use the default font, Latin and Cyrillic characters are displayed correctly, but special characters are broken.
However, If I set a custom font (Poppins), it breaks Cyrillic characters too.

## Steps to Reproduce

<!-- You must include full steps to reproduce so that we can reproduce the problem. -->

1. Add the following `TextFormField` (or `TextField`) widget:
```
TextFormField(
  initialValue: "Some text, 閳, 閳, 娉绘噲瑜夋噲璋㈣阿鎳堣戦偑",
  style: GoogleFonts.poppins(),
)
```
2. Run `flutter run -d chrome --release --dart-define=FLUTTER_WEB_USE_SKIA=true`


**Expected results (DomCanvas):** <!-- what did you want to see? -->
![Flutter Demo - Google Chrome 2020-06-02 20 02 07](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/13119003/83548232-1d6b8e00-a50c-11ea-9601-bae326301b6c.png)

**Actual results: (CanvasKit)** <!-- what did you see? -->

- Without custom font:
![Flutter Demo - Google Chrome 2020-06-02 20 00 38](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/13119003/83548366-57d52b00-a50c-11ea-82e8-09c4808415a1.png)

- With custom font:
![Flutter Demo - Google Chrome 2020-06-02 19 59 29](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/13119003/83548344-4db32c80-a50c-11ea-9a0e-04d851fe647a.png)

Title_Description:
Remove use of BundleUtilities in Linux build When switching to CMake for the Linux desktop build I used `BundleUtilities` to create the relocatable folder, as it seemed like a straightforward and relatively error-proof way of getting all the dependent libraries. However, it has some undesirable properties:
- AFAICT there is no way to control where the libraries it copies end up, so they are all just next to the executable, instead of in a `libs` subfolder as the previous Make build structure used. While not a big deal, it makes for a messy folder.
- How it decides what to copy is something of a black box. In theory it doesn't copy system libraries, but how it decides what a system library is doesn't seem to be something we can control. If someone wanted to use any kind of sysroot, for instance, it would copy basically everything.

Since in general having a fully declarative build system works out better than having magical steps, I think using it was the wrong choice. We should instead explicitly declare the libraries we need, and copy them ourselves.

The necessary changes I'm aware of:
- Set the rpath, which `BundleUtilities` currently does for us. IIRC `CMAKE_INSTALL_RPATH` worked when I was first experimenting with different approaches, but if not we can do it directly in the build as we used to in the Makefile. (The unbundled version isn't launchable anyway, so the rpath of the unbundled copy of the binary doesn't matter.)
- Copy the Flutter library. Prior my adopting `BundleUtilities` I just had the path to the library as another variable exported to parent scope by `flutter/CMakeLists.txt` (it already exports a couple of things).
- Copy the plugin libraries, and do so in a way that allows plugins to add other libraries to that list and have them copied. (While I think in general things will work out better in the ecosystem if plugins statically link their non-system dependencies, that won't always be viable; e.g., a plugin wrapping a binary-only SDK library.) My preference for how to do that is to establish an "API" convention that each plugin exports something like `<plugin_name>_bundled_libraries` to parent scope, which is a list of absolute paths of libraries to copy (including the build product of the plugin itself), and then have the generated_plugins.cmake assemble that into a mega-list that it then exports in turn to its parent scope (the top-level CMake file), which uses it for copying.

A couple of notes on approaches that would be simpler, but that I don't want to use:
- Have plugin builds manipulate the mega-list directly, which would be trivial. This increases the chances that plugin authors will break things in hard-to-find ways. As a simple example, if plugin A accidentally *sets*, rather than appends to, the list, then it'll work fine in isolated testing, but when someone tries to build with plugin A and plugin B, the error will be that plugin *B*'s library is missing on launch, which will cause a lot of extra headache for users and other plugin authors. Having a policy that plugin build files should only make local changes, and export things up, will be much safer for the ecosystem. (Yes, people can still break things at the top level other ways, but I don't want to normalize things that can do that, like changing outside variables.)
- Having the copying done by an install directive in each plugin's build file (e.g., by providing a variable from the top level for a directory to copy into). My concern with this is that it puts more control about the actual behavior into the plugin build files, and once plugins are published we lose the ability to easily make any changes. The more we can have plugins export information about themselves rather than embed logic, the more flexibility we will have to make changes even after the ecosystem is established.

/cc @MarcusTomlinson

Creator: stuartmorgan

Title_Description:
Fix or suppress remaining Windows engine warnings The Windows host engine build's stdout from a bot is currently about 125MB, and 1.6 million lines, because it has 250,000 warnings. This makes looking for errors閳ユ攼r even just loading it閳ユ敁uite painful.

Main categories:
- ~249,000: ~`specified path differs in case from file name on disk` [This](https://github.com/google/skia/blob/master/gn/BUILD.gn#L387) suggests this is a goma issue, and we just need to suppress the warning.~ [Fixed](https://github.com/flutter/buildroot/pull/375)
- ~900: ~`The POSIX name for this item is deprecated`. Almost all from Dart, mostly `strdup`. The fix is either to suppress them, or wrap them, as discussed in https://dart-review.googlesource.com/c/sdk/+/134781~ [Fixed](https://dart-review.googlesource.com/c/sdk/+/142704)
- ~150: ~`no newline at end of file`. All (or very close to all) from ANGLE. Ideally we should just fix that upstream.~ [Fixed](https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/angle/angle/+/2247486).

After that it's just about 20 miscellaneous warnings, mostly conversion warnings in Dart and ANGLE. It would be nice to fix them, but 20 warnings would be a lot better than 250,000

Hello,
I have implemented image_picker plugin, but everytime i pick an image, it restart the application without log or error.
However : 

- when i run it on emulator, it works fine. But as soon as I try it (in debug mode or not) on my smartphone, it restart the app.

- When i run it on my smartphone, using the debugger and going step by step, it works fine.

My phone : Galaxy S7
Android 8.0.0

My emulator : Nexus 5
Android 7.1.1

Below is my code

addImage.dart

import 'dart:io';

import 'package:flutter/material.dart';
import 'package:image_picker/image_picker.dart';

class AddImage extends StatefulWidget {
  @override
  _AddImageState createState() => _AddImageState();
}

class _AddImageState extends State<AddImage> {


  @override
  void initState() {
    super.initState();
  }

  @override
  void dispose() {
    super.dispose();
  }

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    File imageFile;
    final picker = ImagePicker();

    Widget _buildPictureDisplayer(){
      if(imageFile == null){
        return Text('no selected image');
      }else{
        return Column(
          children: <Widget>[
            Image.file(imageFile),
          ],
        );
      }
      
    }

    void _getImageFromGallery() async {
      
      try {

        PickedFile pickedFile = await picker.getImage(source: ImageSource.gallery);

        this.setState(() {
          imageFile = File(pickedFile.path);
        });

      } catch (e) {

        print(e);
      }

    }

    return Scaffold(
      appBar: AppBar(
        title: Text("add image"),
      ),
      body: Center(
        child: Column(
          mainAxisAlignment: MainAxisAlignment.center,
          children: <Widget>[
            IconButton(icon: Icon(Icons.add_a_photo), onPressed: _getImageFromGallery),
            _buildPictureDisplayer(),
          ],
        ),
      ),// This trailing comma makes auto-formatting nicer for build methods.
    );
  }
}
```

Title_Description:
Commit 38c33d9 ModalRoute not rendering color Hi, I had accidentally set my Flutter channel to master and when flutter updated I found that a ModalRoute I'm using in my app was no longer setting its color and was appearing transparent until something causes it to reload (the content is static so this only happened on hot reload).

I am quite new to Flutter and Dart so it might be that I'm using the ModalRoute incorrectly but I'm raising an issue because the change appears to have altered the rendering of the component.


In my code the getter for barrierColor is set to return from an internal variable which is set when buildPage is called so that it is able to get the color from the theme from the context passed to the buildPage function. This seems to not be getting called as it has done previously so the barrierColor gets left as null so the modal renders as transparent.

Flutter documentation states that if the barrierColor getter may change output then to call changedInternalState() but this feels counterintuitive as the state isn't changing and the color isn't known until buildPage is called. In my app the color for the ModalRoute would only change if the device enters dark mode.


In trying to resolve this before realising I was on the wrong channel I had been toying with the idea of passing the color directly to my ModalRoute through its constructor, but the ModalRoute is pushed to the navigator from a component which doesn't have context through async_redux so this would require me to handle the color or theme data through the application state and my gut feeling is that I'd be more likely to introduce bugs through doing this.

The commit to the master branch in the subject may account for the issues I've found as its comments talk about rendering routes less and coincides with my update. Switching back to Flutter stable has resolved this.

https://github.com/flutter/flutter/pull/58202
Labels: framework;severe: performance;passed first triage;perf: speed;P4
Creator: unknownconstant

Title_Description:
EmbeddedViewParams should provide the rect for the embedded view. `EmbeddedViewParams` should remove `offsetPixels` since it's not useful, and instead compute the view rect based on the mutator stack.

This can be done by computing a matrix based on the mutator stack and then multiply it by the matrix [0, 0, width, height]. The final x, y, width, height should be the rect of the embedded view.

Also, this needs better documentation.
Labels: engine;P4
Creator: blasten

Title_Description:
閳藉偊绗 Add support for ARM macOS host Umbrella issue tracking developing Flutter on macOS ARM.
Use case: developer buys ARM Mac, installs Flutter tooling on the Mac, deploys Flutter to an iPhone.

- Build tool on macOS ARM
- Build ARM host dependencies (iproxy, libimobiledevice).  Rosetta translation?
- IDE support
- Infrastructure support

Note: this is tracking host-side issues.  Running Flutter on ARM macOS as a target is tracked by https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/60113.

Wiki page: https://github.com/flutter/flutter/wiki/Developing-with-Flutter-on-Apple-Silicon

Update: Flutter should be fully working on M1 with Rosetta translation (particularly tooling and iOS simulator).  The remaining work is to get it working natively without Rosetta.

### Infrastructure
- [x] https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/87508 Add Mac M1 ARM machines to the prod pool

### Native host development (`flutter` tool)
- [x] https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/84453 
- [ ] https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/69157 (ios-deploy, libimobiledevice, etc)
- [x] https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/86926
- [x] https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/97658 
- [ ] https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/101138

### Completed

#### Sub-issues
- [x] https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/84601 Update iOS and macOS engine builders to Xcode 12.0
- [x] https://github.com/flutter/flutter/pull/60119 [flutter_tools] separate target platform, host platform, and architecture
- [x] https://github.com/dart-lang/sdk/issues/42534 Building flutter tool on ARM macOS host fails
- [x] https://github.com/dart-lang/sdk/issues/42773 Dart SDK version is built for macOS ARM host
- [x] https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/96745 Support building the engine on macOS ARM hosts

#### Physical devices
- [x] https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/65133 "flutter build ios" fails on ARM macOS, ibtoold crashes compiling xcassets/storyboards
- [x] https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/65976#issuecomment-717523043 Add macOS architecture to doctor output for host
- [x] https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/79430 Add mac m1 machines to the staging pool

#### Simulator
- [x] https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/85062 iOS engine artifacts Flutter.xcframework contains old architecture triples directories
- [x] https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/84672 Update Flutter Engine recipes to handle ARM64 simulator 
- [x] https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/82736 Adding ARM iOS simulator times out the engine artifacts build
- [x] https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/66926 engine gn updates required for simulator on macOS arm
- [x] [b/162290052](https://b.corp.google.com/issues/162290052) Cannot launch Android emulators
- [x] https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/60109 Distribute engine as Flutter.xcframework
- [x] https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/69718 Deprecate `flutter build ios-framework --universal`
- [x] https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/65901 XCode SDK needs to be updated on mac LUCI builders
- [x] https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/66925 flutter engine on iOS arm simulator does not build
- [x] https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/73066 Update engine script create_ios_framework to optionally take ARM simulator path
- [x] https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/84670 Add buildroot support for ARM64 simulator engine builds
- [x] https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/69334 Add ARM simulator architecture slice to App.framework to support Apple Silicon
- [x] https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/64502 Flutter cannot build against iOS ARM simulators (on ARM macOS host)
- [x] https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/85713 When plugins do not support ARM iOS simulators, the app fails to build

#### Plugin support
- [x] https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/70796 Work around ffi "symbol not found" error from CocoaPods
- [x] https://github.com/ffi/ffi/issues/800 SEVG on Apple silicon macOS
- [x] https://github.com/invertase/firestore-ios-sdk-frameworks/issues/16 firestore-ios-sdk-frameworks pre-built xcframeworks should support Apple Silicon ARM simulators
- [x] https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/73686 CocoaPods Rosetta workaround has issues
- [x] https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/87242 Mark google_maps_flutter as not supporting arm64 iOS simulator
- [x] https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/87243 Mark google_sign_in as not supporting arm64 iOS simulators
- [x] https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/85713

Tracking Apple Silicon as a target device separately at https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/60113.

Title_Description:
[iOS] FontSubset error: Font subsetting failed with exit code 255 <!-- Thank you for using Flutter!

     If you are looking for support, please check out our documentation
     or consider asking a question on Stack Overflow:
      * https://flutter.dev/
      * https://api.flutter.dev/
      * https://stackoverflow.com/questions/tagged/flutter?sort=frequent

     If you have found a bug or if our documentation doesn't have an answer
     to what you're looking for, then fill our the template below. Please read
     our guide to filing a bug first: https://flutter.dev/docs/resources/bug-reports
-->

## Steps to Reproduce

0. Switch your flutter channel to beta (1.19.0-4.2.pre, which is the up-to-date beta)
1. Checkout https://github.com/suztomo/flutter-font-subsetting-failed. This main.dart contains the following code
```
void main() {
  runApp(MyApp());
}

class MyApp extends StatelessWidget {
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return MaterialApp(
        home: TextFormField(
      decoration: InputDecoration(
        // This fails: Target release_ios_bundle_flutter_assets failed:
        // FontSubset error: Font subsetting failed with exit code 255.
        icon: const Icon(CommunityMaterialIcons.pound_box),
        labelText: 'hello',
      ),
    ));
  }
}
```
2. Run the command below:
```
$ cd ios 
$ pod install 
$ flutter build ios      
   ```
3. You'll see the error `Target release_ios_bundle_flutter_assets failed: FontSubset error: Font subsetting failed with exit code 255.` (detail below)

**Expected results:** <!-- what did you want to see? -->

The build succeeds.

**Actual results:** <!-- what did you see? -->

The build fails with `Target release_ios_bundle_flutter_assets failed: FontSubset error: Font subsetting failed with exit code 255.` (detail below)

From my perspective, several things are broken in Flutter beta:
- I didn't specify "font subset", but somehow it tried to perform that operation.
- It could't perform "font subset" due to exit code 255 (???).
- The error message is obscure; it does not give me any indication on which file is wrong. I had to spend 1 day to identify the problematic piece of code is the input decoration with CommunityMaterialIcons.

# Workaround

See https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/60325#issuecomment-649900131

Title_Description:
MouseRegion no longer reports events when overflowed We rely on being able to place a MouseRegion anywhere in the app and detect enter/exit in that region. This helps us work around cases where the hit area needs to be different from the layout.

Is there any plan to make it toggleable to use the old hit test system or some way to permit overflow of the regions?

https://github.com/flutter/flutter/commit/6f4c4b3cf814648a644406f8d1011e7b6e0e9130#diff-429547c5504ba4c5dad4aac0d88e6c65

Creator: luigi-rosso

Title_Description:
Implement UI TextStyle foreground paint for web It appears that the `foreground` paint property of `TextStyle` from the `dart:ui` package is either unimplemented or buggy for web.

Consider the following code snippet:

```
final ui.ParagraphBuilder paragraphBuilder = ui.ParagraphBuilder(
      ui.ParagraphStyle(
        textAlign: TextAlign.center,
        maxLines: 1,
      ),
    )
      ..pushStyle(ui.TextStyle(
        foreground: paint,
        fontSize: fontSize,
      ))
      ..addText(label);
```

When I provide a gradient for `paint` that goes from transparent, to white, to transparent, the text renders solid black. It should render all or partially white as per the given `paint` gradient.

If I remove the `foreground` property then I see text painted in a different color, which suggests that the issue is that particular property.

```
Flutter 1.20.0-8.0.pre.40 閳 channel master 閳 https://github.com/flutter/flutter.git
Framework 閳 revision 6eaaf1650e (25 hours ago) 閳 2020-07-09 18:04:37 -0700
Engine 閳 revision 9b3e3410f0
Tools 閳 Dart 2.9.0 (build 2.9.0-20.0.dev 06cb010247)
```

Title_Description:
Flutter should have a ScrollbarTheme ## Use case

Add options to customize the appearance of the Scrollbar widget.

Original feedback: https://github.com/flutter/website/issues/4306#issuecomment-656468600

## Proposal

Add options to allow customizing:

- width
- color
- rounded border

The scrollbar should also change color to white when a dark theme is used https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/61364
Labels: new feature;framework;f: scrolling;proposal;P4
Creator: johnpryan

Title_Description:
Multiple webviews disappear at random Unfortunately this is not easily reproducible(I myself cannot reproduce, but 30% of my users report it), but I have an IndexedStack where each child is a webview. The user, via controls on the app, is able to flip through webviews so that one is displayed at a time and the other ones(being children of an IndexedStack) are hidden. 

Problem is that sometimes when users flip to a webview in the IndexedStack, they aren't there -- the webview is totally blank as if it wasn't there(I have done extensive debugging to verify that it is indeed there on the widget tree side). Sometimes refreshing it brings it back, sometimes not. Its as if they fall asleep when in the background. 

Any thoughts?
Labels: platform-ios;engine;plugin;customer: crowd;a: platform-views;p: webview;perf: memory;has reproducible steps;found in release: 1.17;P4;found in release: 1.21
Creator: owenkealey

Title_Description:
Google TOS requires explicit consent Having just installed Flutter on Ubuntu using Snap, my first command was to configure Flutter to disable analytics. I was pretty horrified to see that this downloads more software directly from Google and then claims I have consented to the Google Terms of Service after the fact without even visiting any Google site. Clearly this is not a legally binding contract since I was neither informed in advance nor given any opportunity to the reverse the procedure. At the very least you need to implement a "Do you agree (yes/no)?" prompt in order to claim any form of informed consent here. 

Trying to revoke my consent, I failed to find any contact information on the flutter.dev website, and their "privacy" link just points to the general Google Privacy (or lack thereof) Policy which I obviously find totally unacceptable, and also has no point of contact or GDPR deletion request procedure if you don't have a Google account. What exactly is the procedure If one doesn't agree with the TOS? Deleting the source code tree makes little sense if executables have been installed elsewhere.

Anyway, as I'm sure you know, anyone can fork the Flutter codebase, remove the TOS requirement and distribute the fork as allowed by the BSD license. Situations like these are exactly the reason why FOSS was invented in the first place. Why anyone would have to accept a service TOS to compile and run a piece of open source software on their own computer is beyond me. If Google is commited to the open source movement in anything but lip service they should not demand users sell their privacy in order to use their software (something which they often have little choice in due to employer or client contracts).

Title_Description:
Android nav bar appearing after screen tap when only SystemUiOverlay.top is set When calling `SystemChrome.setEnabledSystemUIOverlays([SystemUiOverlay.top])` in a new Flutter project (in `main()`, `initState()` or `build()` doesn't matter) the Android navigation bar is correctly hidden. However, every (first) tap on the screen, when the navigation bar is hidden, is consumed and the navigation bar appears. It also doesn't hide automatically. If I call `SystemChrome.setEnabledSystemUIOverlays([SystemUiOverlay.top])` again, i.e. when navigating to a new screen, the navigation bar hides. But now we are in the same starting situation where the first tap in consumed and the navigation bar appears again... Another small issue is that with `SystemChrome.setEnabledSystemUIOverlays([SystemUiOverlay.bottom])` the statusbar doesn't auto hide after trigger it to show (swipe on top of screen). Example gifs:
Only status bar [SystemUiOverlay.top]

First tap on the Floating Action Button is consumed by... I don't know what. And for some reason the navigation bar appears. After the navigation bar has appeared the button is tappable and the navigation bar does not auto hide.
Only navigation bar [SystemUiOverlay.bottom]

This does work as expected. Up until triggering the status bar to show. It does not auto hide anymore.
Hide both status and navigation bar []

This works as expected and after a swipe to trigger either to show, they auto hide.

Title_Description:
Inline the templatized "see also" doc entries in slider_theme.dart There are a few problems with our heavy use of templates in the "see also" bullets in [`slider_theme.dart`](https://github.com/flutter/flutter/blob/master/packages/flutter/lib/src/material/slider_theme.dart):

1. They cause problems when rendered to HTML: ![r7JVtUbU0tv](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/15253456/88976226-8ce1cd80-d270-11ea-80e4-f43154c0a2a3.png)
1. Paraphrasing @Hixie: if we're copying our "see also" entries that much, then we may be using too many to make them useful, and we're likely making them less relevant at the local level than we should be.

Can we inline them, and ensure that each inlined version uses verbiage that is locally relevant to its context?
Labels: easy fix;framework;f: material design;d: api docs;entertaining new contributor project;documentation;passed first triage;P4
Creator: tvolkert

Title_Description:
Switch from `amberctl get_up` to `pkgctl resolve` While the transition from `amberctl` to `pkgctl` is still in progress, there is a relatively simple change that can be made:
`amberctl get_up -n <package name>`
becomes
`pkgctl resolve fuchsia-pkg://fuchsia.com/<package name>`

This transition will allow Fuchsia to more quickly drop deprecated commands from the API surface area.
Labels: customer: fuchsia;platform-fuchsia;team: infra;passed secondary triage;P4
Creator: nekorevend

Title_Description:
Android 10 incorrect insets when navigation bar is translucent First of all thanks for the great Flutter toolkit if you'll have some follow up questions to the issue, I'll be glad to answer.

## Steps to Reproduce

The example app is available here: https://github.com/jacek-marchwicki/flutter-insets-bug

Changes to the example project that are necessary to reproduce the issue: https://github.com/jacek-marchwicki/flutter-insets-bug/commit/f23e6d89da417a7ee28dc4f745ddb32d7eec103a
<details>
  <summary>Diff</summary>

```patch
Index: lib/main.dart
IDEA additional info:
Subsystem: com.intellij.openapi.diff.impl.patch.CharsetEP

===================================================================

+++ lib/main.dart	(date 1597401415000)
@@ -72,6 +72,25 @@

+            icon: Icon(Icons.home),

@@ -1,7 +1,17 @@
 package com.example.insetstest
 
+import android.graphics.Color
+import android.os.Build
+import android.view.View
 import io.flutter.embedding.android.FlutterActivity
 
-class MainActivity : FlutterActivity() {
-
+class MainActivity: FlutterActivity() {
+    override fun onWindowFocusChanged(hasFocus: Boolean) {
+        super.onWindowFocusChanged(hasFocus)
+        if (Build.VERSION.SDK_INT >= Build.VERSION_CODES.LOLLIPOP) {
+            window.decorView.systemUiVisibility = View.SYSTEM_UI_FLAG_LAYOUT_HIDE_NAVIGATION or View.SYSTEM_UI_FLAG_LAYOUT_STABLE
+            window.navigationBarColor = Color.TRANSPARENT
+            window.statusBarColor = Color.TRANSPARENT
+        }
+    }
 }

```

</details>

   1. We need to enable transparent navigation bar. According to (the Android documentation: https://developer.android.com/training/gestures/gesturenav) we need to set:
       ```kotlin
            window.decorView.systemUiVisibility = View.SYSTEM_UI_FLAG_LAYOUT_HIDE_NAVIGATION or View.SYSTEM_UI_FLAG_LAYOUT_STABLE
            window.navigationBarColor = Color.TRANSPARENT
            window.statusBarColor = Color.TRANSPARENT
       ```
      
  2. We need to check if insets are updated correctly, In the example I'm using BottomNavigationBar but we could also use SafeArea to reproduce the same issue.


| **Expected results** | **Actual results** | **Actual results** | **On iOS** |
|---|---|---|---|
| We should see the BottomNavigationBar displayed right above system navigation bar. | We see system navigation bar displayed on BottomNavigationBar. | On Android, we can observe the same results when gestures navigation is disabled and standard 3 buttons navigation is set. | The same code works perfectly fine on iOS |
| ![android-with-fix](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/689211/90238803-cc8ae680-de26-11ea-8c6e-625199699ec8.png) | ![android](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/689211/90238895-f6440d80-de26-11ea-9d5b-f4715ebaf70a.png) | ![android-no-gestures](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/689211/90240521-afa3e280-de29-11ea-9803-2c78a3f915d6.png) | ![ios](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/689211/90239030-33100480-de27-11ea-9fea-778fe20a3226.png) |


# Findings

After debugging I found out that Android sets `Window.viewInsets.bottom` to the height of the navigation bar. 
The different is on iOS where `Window.viewInsets.bottom` is set to 0, but the height of the navigation bar is set in `Window.padding.bottom` and `Window.padding.viewPadding`. By looking through the [window documentation](https://api.flutter.dev/flutter/dart-ui/Window-class.html) and the following [video](https://flutter.github.io/assets-for-api-docs/assets/widgets/window_padding.mp4) looks like the iOS implementation is correct.

# Workaround

I've created a widget that does workaround the issue: https://github.com/jacek-marchwicki/flutter-insets-bug/commit/f5eb07af06e9cfee2124d97e33aa2e4189e728f9#diff-fe53fad46868a294b309fc85ed138997R143-R168
With the fix, the app looks correctly:

| Gesture navigation | standard 3 buttons navigation |
|---|---|
| ![android-with-fix](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/689211/90240707-11fce300-de2a-11ea-989b-3cfd62a08058.png) | ![android-with-fix-no-gestures](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/689211/90240717-145f3d00-de2a-11ea-8df4-f12160f0c02c.png) |

Title_Description:
Image animation performance regression on Android I noticed a performance regression when switching to the latest stable (1.20). It happens when animating images (for example during hero animation, or when programmatically zooming in/out in something like `InteractiveViewer`). It is particularly noticeable in debug mode, on low-end devices and with larger images (say >5 MB). In profile mode, performances are way better but we can still observe a regression compared to the previous flutter versions.

Specifically, this engine roll brought the issue: https://github.com/flutter/flutter/pull/58751
but I don't know enough about Skia and the engine to dig deeper...

I made a simple repro project:
https://github.com/deckerst/flutter_image_anim_regression

Here's a video record of this repro [built with a recent master commit of Flutter](https://github.com/deckerst/flutter_image_anim_regression/blob/master/records/E5823_DEBUG_Flutter_master_d1583fc_20200815.mp4) (notice the jank), and another record [built with Flutter v1.19.0-3.0.pre](https://github.com/deckerst/flutter_image_anim_regression/blob/master/records/E5823_DEBUG_Flutter_v1.19.0-3.0.pre.mp4) (smooth like butter). Both are records from debug mode, because it's easier to see, but as I said there is also a regression in profile mode.

It happens with physical Android devices and emulators. I can't say whether it happens on iOS.

edit: here's a timeline taken in profile mode with current Flutter master, on a Sony Xperia Z5 Compact (E5823):
[dart_devtools_2020_8_16-1597547958570000.json.zip](https://github.com/flutter/flutter/files/5079918/dart_devtools_2020_8_16-1597547958570000.json.zip)

**Target Platform:**
Android

**Target OS version/browser:**
7.1.1 (API 25), 10 (API 29)

**Devices:**
Sony Xperia Z5 Compact (E5823), Samsung Galaxy S10e (SM-G970N)

Title_Description:
Provide clearer renderer options on the web The web provides two renderer options: HTML (default) and CanvasKit. To enable CanvasKit one must pass the cryptic and elusive `--dart-define=FLUTTER_WEB_USE_SKIA=true` option. Now that the CanvasKit renderer is maturing, let's discuss how to better surface it.

Another issue with this option is that it's all-or-nothing. You are either always in HTML mode or always in CanvasKit mode. One common situation that's not addressed is that apps that are built simultaneously for mobile and desktop form factors have different constraints. Desktop devices (laptops, computers, TVs) tend to have good internet connections but are compute intensive due to larger denser screens. Mobile devices tend to have worse internet connection speeds and are light on widget count/screen ratio. For this use-case we should provide an option that picks the HTML renderer for mobile devices, and CanvasKit for desktop.

Details are in this doc: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1aY0iU16wf_sdT7nwfpjgT-IatHNfF3slTiYHKmxcIog
Labels: tool;engine;platform-web;passed first triage;e: web_html;e: web_canvaskit;P4

Title_Description:
Guidance on keyboard shortcuts for Desktop/Web I want to implement custom keyboard shortcuts for desktop and web in our flutter web.  

For example: 
We are building a school organization app. 
If a user is on the homework page they should be able to create a new homework via `CTRL + N` instead of clicking an extended FAB.

**The problem is that it's even hard to find out if keyboard shortcuts are supported yet**.
Much less how to implement them if they are supported.

Google searches for flutter keyboard shortcuts are often referring to keyboard shortcuts for flutter IDEs.  
There is no (at least I couldn't directly find one) article about keyboard shortcuts.

What I could find:
- https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/31946 "Keyboard shortcuts and actions should be supported." (Closed)
Not much context, it seems like this is only for standard keyboard shortcuts like TAB, ENTER, CTRL-Z and meant as something which helps the Flutter to natively support these. Nothing for me as a developer for my own app to use (from what I understand).
- A Stackoverflow question with no answers: ["How to handle keyboard shortcuts"](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/61960260/how-to-handle-keyboard-shortcuts)
- The [`Shortcuts`](https://api.flutter.dev/flutter/widgets/Shortcuts-class.html)/[`ShortcutManager`](https://api.flutter.dev/flutter/widgets/ShortcutManager-class.html) Widgets with **sub-par documentation**.
There is no context on why these classes exist, what problems they solve and what problems they do not solve.
There are no examples.
I have no idea if these widgets help me or not with my problem.
- The [`keyboard_shortcuts`](https://pub.dev/packages/keyboard_shortcuts) package.
I haven't used it yet, it seems like something that could work. Nonetheless this is a package by a single person for a universal problem which in my opinion should be solved by Flutter.

So my points are that there should be Guidance if keyboard shortcuts are already supported by Flutter.  
If they aren't I would wish for a single ticket for keyboard shortcuts for web and desktop that is easily searchable and where the current state and the the next steps are documented.
If they are there should be documentation on how to implement them with examples.
Labels: a: desktop;documentation;passed first triage;P4
Creator: Jonas-Sander

## Steps to Reproduce

<!-- You must include full steps to reproduce so that we can reproduce the problem. -->

1. Clone https://github.com/memspace/zefyr.git
2. Go to `packages/zefyr/example` and run with `flutter run -d macOS`
3. Click on "Embedded in a form" example
4. In the middle multiple field (that's ZefyrEditor) type in `abc` and press `Enter`

**Expected results:** <!-- what did you want to see? -->

`Enter` should've added a new line

**Actual results:** <!-- what did you see? -->

No new line appears. 
While debugging I noticed that in my `TextInputClient.updateEditingValue` I get unexpected control characters when pressing `Enter` (`13` (`\r`) instead of `10` (`\n`)), `Delete` (adds `8` code unit to the text) and arrow keys also modify the text itself instead of changing selection.

I scanned through the standard EditableTextState implementation and couldn't find anything that would indicate any issues in the way I set up input connection or handle updates.

When I use regular multiline TextField everything looks correct there and no special characters are present.

In the attached logs at the very end I have some `print`ed statements for the raw text code units I receive from the platform side.

```
class MapSample extends StatefulWidget {
  @override
  State<MapSample> createState() => MapSampleState();
}

class MapSampleState extends State<MapSample> {
  final Completer<GoogleMapController> _controller =
      Completer<GoogleMapController>();

  final Set<Marker> _markers = <Marker>{};
  BitmapDescriptor _icon;

  @override
  void initState() {
    super.initState();

    BitmapDescriptor.fromAssetImage(
            ImageConfiguration(), 'assets/images/marker.png')
        .then((BitmapDescriptor onValue) {
      _icon = onValue;
    });
  }

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return GoogleMap(
      onMapCreated: _onMapCreated,
      markers: _markers,
      mapType: MapType.normal,
      initialCameraPosition: CameraPosition(
        target: LatLng(lat, long),
        zoom: 12,
      ),
    );
  }

  void _onMapCreated(GoogleMapController controller) {
    _controller.complete(controller);

    DefaultAssetBundle.of(context)
        .loadString('assets/styles/map_style.json')
        .then((String value) => controller.setMapStyle(value));

    for (final ShopLocationData sld in shops) {
      _markers.add(_createMarker(context, sld));
    }
  }

  Marker _createMarker(BuildContext context, ShopLocationData sld) {
    return Marker(
      markerId: MarkerId(sld.coordinates.toString()),
      position: sld.coordinates,
      infoWindow: InfoWindow(
        title: sld.name,
        snippet: sld.address,
      ),
      icon: _icon, // ERROR
    );
  }
}

Title_Description: [infra] No way to skip builders per-branch on post-submit We currently have no way of skipping builders on post-submit for particular branches (in this case, we would like to skip the Fuchsia builder on all branches except master). Try jobs are scheduled by cocoon based on JSON files in the source repos, however post-submit builders are defined in `flutter/infra`, and are the same across all branches.

Creator: christopherfujino

Title_Description:
Support a local engine flag in the tool integration tests I recently had to debug a regression in the flutter_tools integration tests using a local build of the engine binaries.

I was able to do this by patching `_setupProcess` in https://github.com/flutter/flutter/blob/master/packages/flutter_tools/test/integration.shard/test_driver.dart to add a `--local-engine` flag to the command line that it generated.

It would be useful to have a flag in the test runner that can select a local engine.

@jonahwilliams

Creator: jason-simmons

BUG: google_maps_flutter_web - Polylines not showing up It seems POLYLINES are not supported. I can see it on Mobile but not on the web. 

Here is what my code looks like: 

```dart
  GoogleMap(
        gestureRecognizers: Set()
          ..add(Factory<PanGestureRecognizer>(() => PanGestureRecognizer()))
          ..add(Factory<ScaleGestureRecognizer>(() => ScaleGestureRecognizer()))
          ..add(Factory<TapGestureRecognizer>(() => TapGestureRecognizer()))
          ..add(Factory<VerticalDragGestureRecognizer>(
              () => VerticalDragGestureRecognizer())),
        tiltGesturesEnabled: true,
        myLocationEnabled: true,
        myLocationButtonEnabled: true,
        mapToolbarEnabled: true,
        buildingsEnabled: true,
        markers: _markers,
        polylines: [
          Polyline(
            width: 4,
            polylineId: PolylineId("1"),
            color: userLocation.urgencyColor,
            points: [

              UserLocation.kaaba,

        ].toSet(),
        mapType: widget.mapType,
        zoomGesturesEnabled: true,
        scrollGesturesEnabled: true,
        rotateGesturesEnabled: true,
        compassEnabled: true,
        onMapCreated: _onMapCreated,
        initialCameraPosition: CameraPosition(

    );

Title_Description:
Flutter Web SVG is rendering in Chrome fine, but not Firefox 
## Steps to Reproduce

1. Create a Flutter template app
2. Swap the contents of the `Center` widget with:
```
Image.network(
"data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
height: 70,
width: 70,
)
```

Full repo of the problem can be found here:
https://github.com/jpeiffer/flutter_firefox_svg_issue

SVG renders in all browsers

SVG renders fine in Chrome, but not Firefox

Title_Description:
Wrong Flutter behavior with plugins that throw and catch C++ exceptions ## Steps to Reproduce

<!-- You must include full steps to reproduce so that we can reproduce the problem. -->

1. Run `git clone git@github.com:nonlinear-chaos-order-etc-etal/flutter_plugin_sample.git`.
2. If you run `cd example && flutter run -d Linux` as is, the example crashes after printing "calling FlutterCrashSamplePlugin.sampleMethod()..."

The plugin uses the C++ `throw` keyword to throw an exception on an error condition.

**Expected results:** <!-- what did you want to see? -->

Need some way to ~~use~~ catch C++ exceptions back in Dart code. I tried to add `-fexceptions` to CMake files, this did not help.

Plugin should safely return "error: test_cpp_exception" string to Dart code.

**Actual results:** <!-- what did you see? -->

Flutter app crashes somewhere on C++ `throw` inside the plugin. If we comment out the `throw` line ( https://github.com/nonlinear-chaos-order-etc-etal/flutter_plugin_sample/blob/master/linux/flutter_crash_sample_plugin_plugin.cc#L29 ), C++ plugin safely returns "41!" string.

Title_Description:
[google_maps_flutter_web] Custom BitmapDescriptor for icon in Marker does not appear on web ## Steps to Reproduce

I used this to generate a custom BitmapDescriptor from an icon:
https://gist.github.com/jbxbergdev/5238bb78b03a2a4e6f24e55f442d2b70

Pass that BitmapDescriptor directly into the marker like this:
Marker m = Marker(icon: _customBitmapDescriptor, ...)
markers.add(m)

Pass the marker into the GoogleMap:
GoogleMap(markers: markers, ...)

**Expected results:**
A custom icon for the marker on the google map (based on the Icon passed to MarkerGenerator).

**Actual results:**
The standard red google maps marker is on the map.

-->

## Steps to Reproduce

<!-- You must include full steps to reproduce so that we can reproduce the problem. -->

DraggableScrollableSheet is rebuilding the screen while dragging the sheet and it is causing unnecessary flickers.

```dart
class MyPopUpSheet extends StatelessWidget {
  ScrollController _scrollController; //Needed for

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Material(
      child: DraggableScrollableSheet(
        initialChildSize: 0.4,
        minChildSize: 0.4,
        builder: (ctx, scrollController) {
          
         print('Rebuilding...');

          return CustomScrollView(
            controller: scrollController,
            slivers: [
              SliverToBoxAdapter(child: Container(Colors.deepOrange)),
              SliverToBoxAdapter(child: Container(Colors.red)),
              SliverToBoxAdapter(child: Container(Colors.green)),
            ],
          );
        },
      ),
    );
  }

```

**Expected results:** <!-- what did you want to see? -->
It shouldn't rebuild the widget while dragging the sheet.

Title_Description:
[google_maps_flutter_web] GoogleMapController.getLatLng() does not work `GoogleMapController.getLatLng()` function constantly returns the same strange value `LatLng(85.05112877980659, -180)`. 
At the same time, it works correctly in applications. 

Code:
```
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return GoogleMap(
      initialCameraPosition: const CameraPosition(target: LatLng(0, 0)),
      onMapCreated: (controller) {
        googleMapController = controller;
      },
      onCameraIdle: () async {
        if (googleMapController == null) return;
        debugPrint('getLatLng        ---> ${await googleMapController.getLatLng(ScreenCoordinate(x: 0, y: 0))}');
        debugPrint('getVisibleRegion ---> ${await googleMapController.getVisibleRegion()}');
      },
    );
}
```

Title_Description:
[web] In-Browser Zoom not working with Ctrl + Scroll <!-- Thank you for using Flutter!

     If you are looking for support, please check out our documentation
     or consider asking a question on Stack Overflow:
      * https://flutter.dev/
      * https://api.flutter.dev/
      * https://stackoverflow.com/questions/tagged/flutter?sort=frequent

     If you have found a bug or if our documentation doesn't have an answer
     to what you're looking for, then fill out the template below. Please read
     our guide to filing a bug first: https://flutter.dev/docs/resources/bug-reports
-->

## Steps to Reproduce

<!-- You must include full steps to reproduce so that we can reproduce the problem. -->

1. Run `flutter create bug`
2. Hold `Ctrl` and `scroll wheel up/down`

**Expected results:** <!-- what did you want to see? -->
Browser should adjust its zoom level in or out.

**Actual results:** <!-- what did you see? -->
Browser did not adjust its zoom level.

<details>
  <summary>Logs</summary>

<!-- Finally, paste the output of running `flutter doctor -v` here. -->

```
[閳姝 Flutter (Channel beta, 1.23.0-18.1.pre, on Microsoft Windows [Version    10.0.18363.1139], locale en-US)
    閳 Flutter version 1.23.0-18.1.pre at
      C:\Users\Brayden\Documents\SDK\flutter
    閳 Framework revision 198df796aa (4 days ago), 2020-10-15 12:04:33    
      -0700
    閳 Engine revision 1d12d82d9c
    閳 Dart version 2.11.0 (build 2.11.0-213.1.beta)

 
[閳姝 Android toolchain - develop for Android devices (Android SDK version 
    29.0.3)

[閳姝 Android Studio (version 4.0)
    閳 Android Studio at C:\Program Files\Android\Android Studio
    閳 Flutter plugin version 49.0.2

    閳 Java version OpenJDK Runtime Environment (build
      1.8.0_242-release-1644-b01)

[閳姝 VS Code, 64-bit edition (version 1.49.1)
    閳 VS Code at C:\Program Files\Microsoft VS Code

    閳 Edge (web)       閳 edge       閳 web-javascript 閳 Microsoft Edge    
      86.0.622.38

```

</details>

Notes:
- `Ctrl` + `-` & `Ctrl` + `+` work, this seems specifically to an issue with the default scroll wheel behavior being ignored. 
- I tried looking into it on the engine code and found this: 

> engine\lib\web_ui\lib\src\engine\pointer_binding.dart

ln 493
```dart
    _addWheelEventListener((html.Event event) {
      assert(event is html.WheelEvent);
      if (_debugLogPointerEvents) {
        print(event.type);
      }
      _callback(_convertWheelEventToPointerData(event as html.WheelEvent));
      // Prevent default so mouse wheel event doesn't get converted to
      // a scroll event that semantic nodes would process.
      event.preventDefault();
    });
```

ln 772
```dart
    _addWheelEventListener((html.Event event) {
      assert(event is html.WheelEvent);
      if (_debugLogPointerEvents) {
        print(event.type);
      }
      _callback(_convertWheelEventToPointerData(event as html.WheelEvent));
      // Prevent default so mouse wheel event doesn't get converted to
      // a scroll event that semantic nodes would process.
      event.preventDefault();
    });
```

Maybe these event preventions are blocking the default browser behavior? Just a guess.

Title_Description:
flutter/packages builds are not hermetic flutter/packages .cirrus config fetches directly from latest master and uses `pub global activate` to install `flutter_plugin_tools`. A build that succeeds at one point in time can fail next time at the same commit simply by fetching a different version of Flutter or plugin tools ([example build breakage](https://github.com/flutter/packages/pull/234)).

Culprit: https://github.com/flutter/packages/blob/85135ddad047d82aa5025496410a41b031c4c5df/.cirrus.yml#L7-L11
Labels: team;package;passed first triage;team: infra;passed secondary triage;P4
Creator: yjbanov

Title_Description:
Extra character while writing LTR and RTL languages in a text field ## Steps to Reproduce

1. create an empty application
2. add one text field to the application
3. (optional) you can make its obscure equals to true to see the problem better by seeing the count of dots
4. type something in English
5. change the language of your keyboard (we tested by Persian) and type another thing
6. use space
7. u must see another character is being written beside the space (we check the ASCII code and believe it is half space)

from several observation and tests, I believe this problem is happening when you are writing an LTR language inside an LTR field then you use an RTL language inside the same field (or vice-versa with the RTL field), and when it occurred if u even delete all the character and write again with only one language it still happening.

summary:
u have a LTR filed -> write LTR language (it's still ok) -> write RTL -> use space
or
u have an RTL field -> write RTL language (it's still ok) -> write LTR -> use space 

> note: because the half-space character is not visual and doesn't persist any spaces between characters you may want to use shift + right arrow and select the characters to feel it.

> note: this has been happening since flutter version 1.17 and because of that we have to use 1.12.13+hotfix6

it is a bit confusing when it comes to writing on a paper so u can see this video for a better understanding


![ezgif-6-fd79323b979e](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/7807264/97110996-7e7d4380-16f1-11eb-8128-78174ce53bf2.gif)

Title_Description:
Text selection using keyboard doesn't work on Windows ## Description
On Windows, text selection using keyboard doesn't work. 
Possibly after the selection is correctly updated by the framework in _handleKeyEvent() in Editable, it's overwritten by a change from the embedding - similarly to [#22063](https://github.com/flutter/engine/pull/22063).

## Steps to Reproduce

1. Run `flutter create texttest`.
2. Update main.dart adding a TextField:
* in class _MyHomePageState: 
```
  final _controller = TextEditingController();
```
* in the Scaffold list <Widget>[:
```
              TextField(
                controller: _controller,
                decoration: InputDecoration(
                  labelText: 'Test',
                  hintText: 'Enter some text'
                ),
              ),    
```
3. Run

**Expected results:** after typing some text in the field, use Shift+LeftArrow to select it

## Steps to Reproduce

<!-- You must include full steps to reproduce so that we can reproduce the problem. -->
I've only tested this on Flutter Web in MacOS.

1. Create a Draggable widget.
2. Right click on the Draggable widget.
3. Dismiss the right click menu by clicking anywhere
4. Move the mouse around

Reproducible code sample:
```
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';

void main() {
  runApp(MyApp());
}

class MyApp extends StatelessWidget {
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return MaterialApp(
      home: Scaffold(
        body: Center(child: MyDraggable()),
      ),
    );

}

Title_Description:
[feature_request] Disable scrolling by drag with a mouse ## Use case

When having long text field in web, it is very hard to select the text without making unintentional drag and scroll.

## Proposal

Give possibility to disable scrolling by dragging, but leave enabled scrolling by scroll event.
In theory it could be done by listening the scroll event and NeverScrolllabePhysics, but at the same time it does not follow text field position (so writing in text field does not scroll the page, because of NeverScrollablePhysics).
Labels: new feature;framework;f: scrolling;platform-web;proposal;passed first triage;P4
Creator: mordivgor

Title_Description:
Linux/GTK: Mouse wheel scrolling is slow on Wayland ## Steps to Reproduce

1. Run https://flathub.org/apps/search/fluffychat on a Linux x64 desktop (I use GNOME Shell in Wayland mode, in case that should be relevant)
2. Scroll in the chat log, the chat list, or the settings listing

**Expected results:**  mouse wheel scrolling is super slow, not laggy but the speed is just *way too low*. like, it's really bad. clicking and dragging is fine but that is a very clumsy gesture with a mouse (as opposed to a finger on a touch device)

**Actual results:** scrolls as fast as all the other applications I use on linux. some of them differ a little in scrolling speed, but all of them - outside of fluffychat/flutter - are acceptable.

Title_Description:
[Proposal][video_player]: Make Readme IOS Permissions optional Why is there the recommendation to add this into the Podfile?

```
<key>NSAppTransportSecurity</key>
<dict>
  <key>NSAllowsArbitraryLoads</key>
  <true/>
</dict>
``` 

This can be a security nightmare for all Apps using this. Just have a look at this:
https://stackoverflow.com/questions/31254725/transport-security-has-blocked-a-cleartext-http

Please remove this or mark it as `not recommended`

Title_Description:
DomParagraph _tryBuildPlainText should not default `color` For example, this program will fail on web:

```dart
import 'dart:ui';

void main() {
  final ParagraphBuilder builder = ParagraphBuilder(ParagraphStyle());
  builder.pushStyle(TextStyle(foreground: Paint()..color = const Color(0xFFABCDEF)));
  builder.addText('hi');
  final Paragraph paragraph = builder.build(); // assertion error
  print(paragraph);
}
```

```
dart_sdk.js:4205 Uncaught (in promise) Error: Assertion failed: org-dartlang-sdk:///flutter_web_sdk/lib/_engine/engine/text/paragraph.dart:949:13
color == null || foreground == null
"Cannot provide both a color and a foreground\nThe color argument is just a shorthand for \"foreground: new Paint()..color = color\"."
    at Object.throw_ [as throw] (dart_sdk.js:4205)
    at Object.assertFailed (dart_sdk.js:4151)
    at new _engine.EngineTextStyle.only (dart_sdk.js:160215)
    at _engine.DomParagraphBuilder.new.[_tryBuildPlainText] (dart_sdk.js:160439)
    at _engine.DomParagraphBuilder.new.build (dart_sdk.js:160353)
    at Object.main$0 [as main] (<anonymous>:70:29)
    at main$ (<anonymous>:57:12)
    at main$.next (<anonymous>)
    at dart_sdk.js:36192
    at _RootZone.runUnary (dart_sdk.js:36060)
    at _FutureListener.thenAwait.handleValue (dart_sdk.js:31289)
    at handleValueCallback (dart_sdk.js:31804)
    at Function._propagateToListeners (dart_sdk.js:31842)
    at async._AsyncCallbackEntry.new.callback (dart_sdk.js:31579)
    at Object._microtaskLoop (dart_sdk.js:36297)
    at _startMicrotaskLoop (dart_sdk.js:36303)
    at dart_sdk.js:32051
```

The problem is at https://github.com/flutter/engine/blob/91ec9451dd3fb1d5424dc4551653774541640931/lib/web_ui/lib/src/engine/text/paragraph.dart#L1331 - I'm not quite clear on the implications of changing that though. At any rate, if the foreground property is specified we can't specify the color.

/cc @hterkelsen @yjbanov @mdebbar 
/cc @grooviz - this is the cause of https://github.com/dnfield/flutter_svg/issues/463
Labels: engine;a: typography;e: web_html;assigned for triage;P4
Creator: dnfield

Title_Description:

  # TODO(mvanbeusekom): Temporary disabled until web is migrated to nnbd (advised by @blasten).

```

---

I just figured it would be good to **document** this because it was non-trivial to figure this out.

Title_Description:
Update engine script create_ios_framework to optionally take ARM simulator path In preparation for [an ARM simulator framework](https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/64502) update [create_ios_framework](https://github.com/flutter/engine/blob/06f9654c67f80711a8c7970ede61c328bdf999a6/sky/tools/create_ios_framework.py#L23) to replace `--simulator-out-dir` with `--simulator-x86-out-dir` and `--simulator-arm64-out-dir`.  `lipo` the simulator frameworks together.

When that's done, update the [recipe logic that calls this script](https://flutter.googlesource.com/recipes/+/refs/heads/master/recipes/engine.py#1104) to pass in `--simulator-x86-out-dir`. 
 When https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/64502 is ready, it will additionally pass in `--simulator-arm64-out-dir`.

Don't remove deprecated `--simulator-out-dir` until after the recipe is updated to avoid breaking changes.

Title_Description:
Holding backspace in textfield stops sporadically on Samsung devices ## Steps to Reproduce

1. Run `flutter create bug`.
2. Update main.dart as follows : . 


<details>
<summary>code sample</summary>

```dart
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';

void main() {
  runApp(MyApp());
}

class MyApp extends StatelessWidget {
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return MaterialApp(
      title: 'Flutter Demo',
      theme: ThemeData(
        primarySwatch: Colors.blue,
      ),
      home: MyHomePage(title: 'Flutter Demo Home Page'),
    );
  }
}

class MyHomePage extends StatefulWidget {
  MyHomePage({Key key, this.title}) : super(key: key);

  final String title;

  @override
  _MyHomePageState createState() => _MyHomePageState();
}

class _MyHomePageState extends State<MyHomePage> {
  TextEditingController _controller;

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Scaffold(
      appBar: AppBar(
        title: Text(widget.title),
      ),
      body: TextField(
        controller: _controller,
      ),
    );
  }
}
```
</details>




3. Run app on a Samsung S8 or Samsung A8 - potentially oher devices or just the samsung keyboard.
4. Type the phrase "fire crystal", hold the backspace key. (seems to happen with any text that has multiple words though)

**Expected results:** 
Text should continue get deleted until the field is empty or the users lets go out the backspace key. 

**Actual results:** 
Sometimes it will only delete a single character, other times it has deleted back as far as "fir" in the case of the phrase "fire crystal".

Title_Description:
閳藉偊绗  Desktop accessibility support This is an umbrella issue that covers the work being done to support accessibility for desktop Flutter applications.

### Design documents

- go/flutter-desktop-accessibility
- go/accessibility-bridge-detailed-design

### Related issues

- https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/23601

### Flutter Engine Changes

- [x] Forked chromium accessibility code https://github.com/flutter/engine/pull/22909
- [x] Initial import of accessibility code from Chromium https://github.com/flutter/engine/pull/23087
- [x] Apply local patch to chromium accessibility code https://github.com/flutter/engine/pull/23110
- [x] Implements accessibility bridge in common library https://github.com/flutter/engine/pull/23491

mac:
- [x] Wires up accessibility bridge in macOS https://github.com/flutter/engine/pull/23870
- [x] selection announcement does not work for selectable text https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/77833
- [x] voice over does not announce feedback when typing in a text field https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/77834
- [x] text field should be activated when it receives a11y focus https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/77835

windows:
- [x] Forked required windows component from chromium https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/77836
- [ ] Wires up accessibility bridge in Windows https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/77838

### Chromium Changes

- https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/2616901
Labels: framework;engine;a: accessibility;a: desktop;passed first triage;P4
Creator: HansMuller

Title_Description:
Focus.onKey(...) callback not updated when parent rebuild ## Steps to Reproduce

When using build method's variable inside a callback, you expect to always have the latest updated value. It's not the case for the `Focus.onKey` callback :

```dart
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';
import 'package:flutter/services.dart';

void main() {
  runApp(MyApp());
}

class MyApp extends StatelessWidget {
  // This widget is the root of your application.
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return MaterialApp(home: MyHomePage());
  }
}

class MyHomePage extends StatefulWidget {
  @override
  _MyHomePageState createState() => _MyHomePageState();
}

class _MyHomePageState extends State<MyHomePage> {
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    final ts = DateTime.now().microsecondsSinceEpoch;
    print("build : $ts");

    return Focus(
      autofocus: true,
      onKey: (_, event) {
        if (event is RawKeyDownEvent &&
            event.logicalKey == LogicalKeyboardKey.enter) {
          print("key : $ts");
        }
        return KeyEventResult.handled;
      },
      child: Column(
        children: [
          OutlinedButton(
            child: Text("rebuild"),
            onPressed: () {
              print("rebuild");
              setState(() {});
            },
          ),
          OutlinedButton(
            child: Text("print"),
            onPressed: () {
              print("pressed : $ts");
            },
          ),
        ],
      ),
    );
  }
}

```


**Expected results:** <!-- what did you want to see? -->

The timestamp value printed from callback should be equals to the last build.

**Actual results:** <!-- what did you see? -->

onKey callback always use the first value, not the last one

rebuild now
build : 1611407226901000
pressed : 1611407226901000
rebuild now
build : 1611407236015000
pressed : 1611407236015000
key : 1611407212102000
```

Title_Description: Move pipeline state object creation outside the frame workload. Today, when the engine needs a unique shader variant to render parts of scene, it is already in the middle of a frame workload. Determining the shader needed, constructing the shader, translating it through the various intermediate formats and finally compiling it before constructing pipeline state objects from it can take multiple frame intervals worth of time. Due to the flexible nature of the Flutter rendering APIs, knowing the entire set of shader variants upfront is not possible. Instead, API affordances must be available for callers to create these shaders outside the frame workload so that their use can be made in frames without jank. This is an umbrella issue tracking the design work necessary for such APIs.
Labels: new feature;engine;customer: crowd;severe: rendering;passed first triage;P4
Creator: chinmaygarde

Title_Description:
FlutterViewController needs a way to correctly start running before being shown on macOS Currently `FlutterViewController` has a private method called `launchEngine` that's called from `viewWillAppear`. That registers internal plugins, starts the engine, and sends the initial settings. There's no public way to trigger that flow, which means that if a developer wants to create a FlutterViewController that's hidden, but start running it, they can't; if they start running the engine directly using engine methods, then it won't get the internal plugins or settings.

We should change the way that non-engine code is triggered, or if that's not viable, add public API to trigger that flow.
Labels: engine;platform-mac;a: desktop;passed first triage;P4
Creator: stuartmorgan

Title_Description:
[cocoon] Create scheduler service flutter/cocoon has several separate locations for scheduling. Unifying it all behind a single service will make it easier to track the scheduling logic Cocoon has.

Currently there are separate request handlers for scheduling initial tasks and retrying these tasks. Instead, there should be a scheduler service the request handlers call.

This will make it cleaner to schedule against webhooks while still supporting the cron methods.

## Checklist
- [X] Create scheduler service - https://github.com/flutter/cocoon/pull/1087
- [X] Schedule prod tasks on GitHub webhook - https://github.com/flutter/cocoon/pull/1109
- [X] Recipes support checkouts from GitHub instead of GoB
- [x] Validate `.ci.yaml` changes in presubmit - https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/79579
- [x] Support presubmit targets - https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/77858
- [x] Prod LUCI tasks are updated - https://github.com/flutter/cocoon/pull/1210
 - [x] Deprecate "validate_json" step: https://flutter.googlesource.com/recipes/+/refs/heads/master/recipe_modules/json_util/api.py
