Camera Plugin Stream is rotated 90 degree on iPhone since 0.7.0 After an upgrade of the Camera Plugin to version 0.7.0 and later, the `CameraImage` from `startImageStream` is 90 degrees CCW rotated.

This leads to unexpected and unfavorable behavior for further processing the CameraImage with MLKit/others.
For example, a user has to turn its smartphone or paper 90 degree ccw in order to get a good result with MLKit on iOS.


## Steps to Reproduce

Please have a look inside this StackOverflow ticket. This includes the source-code as well as the results (from version 0.7.0+2 and 0.6.4+5). Basically it is the Example source code but with `controller.buildPreview()`instead of the `CameraPreview`widget.
[https://stackoverflow.com/questions/66225051/flutter-camera-package-stream-picture-from-camera-is-90-rotated/66243581#66243581
](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/66225051/flutter-camera-package-stream-picture-from-camera-is-90-rotated/66243581#66243581
)

[google_maps_flutter_web] UnimplementedError: updateTileOverlays() has not been implemented. ## Steps to Reproduce

When instantiating and building GoogleMap on flutter web, it triggers a bunch of "Error: UnimplementedError: updateTileOverlays() has not been implemented." errors.

pubspec.yaml
```
dependencies:
  google_maps_flutter: ^1.2.0
  google_maps_flutter_web: ^0.1.1
```

main.dart
```
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';
import 'package:google_maps_flutter/google_maps_flutter.dart';

void main() {
  runApp(MyApp());
}

class MyApp extends StatelessWidget {
  // This widget is the root of your application.
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return MaterialApp(
      title: 'Flutter Demo',
      theme: ThemeData(
        primarySwatch: Colors.blue,
      ),
      home: MyHomePage(title: 'Flutter Demo Home Page'),
    );
  }
}

class MyHomePage extends StatefulWidget {
  MyHomePage({Key key, this.title}) : super(key: key);

  final String title;

  @override
  _MyHomePageState createState() => _MyHomePageState();
}

class _MyHomePageState extends State<MyHomePage> {
  Set<Marker> markers = Set<Marker>();
  

  @override
  void initState() {
    super.initState();    
  }

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Scaffold(
      appBar: AppBar(
        title: Text(widget.title),
      ),
      body: Center(
        child: Column(
          mainAxisAlignment: MainAxisAlignment.center,
          children: <Widget>[

            ),
            SizedBox(

                  target: LatLng(0,0),
                  zoom: 10
                ),

}

Title_Description:
Windows resizing artifacts regression https://github.com/flutter/engine/pull/24428, has caused regression in certain situations. 

Bit of background first. As far as I can tell, the resizing with direct composition enabled was originally broken, because every second call to `CreateSurface` failed. I believe this happens because when recreating the surface, context is still in use, which means a `IDCompositionTarget` instance is still alive. I haven't tried this with UWP, but I was able to get direct composition surface (`EGL_DIRECT_COMPOSITION_ANGLE`) recreated as expected by calling `ClearContext()` right before `DestroySurface()` in `AngleSurfaceManager::ResizeSurface`.

The PR fixed it by only calling `CreateSurface` once and then resizing existing surface. This is done though calling `eglPostSubBufferNV`, which as a side effects resizes underlying surface. The issue here is that `eglPostSubBufferNV` also causes `Swapchain->Present` to be called two additional times during every resize step, with wrong surface size. This is not obvious for windows that have border. DWM simply seems to eat these two extra Present calls.

It does however cause problem for windows that had border removed through `WM_NCCALCSIZE `. It seems that whatever magic DWM does to synchronize swapchain swap with window resize, it gives up once `WM_NCCALCSIZE ` is used. In this case it manifests in those two extra `Present` calls properly executed (including waiting for vsync), which results in content wobbling around during resizing.

The ideal solution here would most likely be to introduce a way in angle to force surface resize, without having additional swaps during resize. The resizing was changed lately to ensure that we only do one swap per resize step (with correct size).

It would be also good to know if maybe we're missing some `ClearContext()` calls, or perhaps it is by design and the `ClearContext()` call should be placed in `ResizeSurface()`. 

If proper solution (surface resize in angle) is a no go, than perhaps, at least temporarily, we could revert this for non UWP target.

cc @clarkezone

Title_Description:
Enable Windows plugin tests for stable branch flutter/plugins runs most tests on both the `master` and `stable` branches of Flutter. That wasn't the case for Windows since it was only available on `master`, but now that it is available on `stable` we should be running the tests there too. I believe this involves modifying the recipe added [here](https://flutter-review.googlesource.com/c/recipes/+/5901)

(See for the first iteration of enabling these tests.)

For all other platforms we can do this within flutter/plugins since they use Cirrus, but AFAIK there's no way to do this in-repo with LUCI (which is used for the Windows tests).

/cc @godofredoc @cbracken
Labels: plugin;platform-windows;a: desktop;team: infra;passed secondary triage;P4
Creator: stuartmorgan

Title_Description:
Add `Picture.toImageSync` that returns `Image` Currently Flutter has `Picture.toImage` returning `Future<Image>` ([api docs](https://api.flutter.dev/flutter/dart-ui/Picture/toImage.html)). The API docs say "Although the image is returned synchronously, the picture is actually rasterized the first time the image is drawn and then cached". This makes me think that wrapping the result in a `Future` is redundant. Can we have a `Picture.toImageSync` that returns the image truly synchronously?

The use-case is procedurally generated atlasses that can be rendered using `Canvas.drawAtlas`. For example, to render particle effects, such as those generated by https://felixblaschke.github.io/liquid-studio, it is more efficient to use an atlas rather than many `drawCircle`s with blurring mask filter. However, to generate the atlas one needs to call `Picture.toImage` and miss at least one frame. `Picture.toImageSync` would allow us to generate an atlas synchronously (and cheaply, since the atlas contains just one particle) and in the same frame render thousands of particles using `drawAtlas`.
Labels: new feature;engine;severe: performance;proposal;passed first triage;perf: speed;e: web_canvaskit;P3;P4
Creator: yjbanov

Title_Description:
[TextInputFormatter] FilteringTextInputFormatter might have some handling mistakes Not sure whether is by design for regexp's match result or a bug.

# Case 1:

## Pattern

`FilteringTextInputFormatter.allow(RegExp(r'^(0|[1-9]{0,4})(\.\d{0,2})?$'))`

## Steps to Reproduce

1. Input `1111.11`.
2. Input another number.

**Expected results:** Keep the original input.

**Actual results:** All inputs are gone.

# Case 2:

## Pattern

`FilteringTextInputFormatter.allow(RegExp(r'^(0|[1-9]{0,4})(\.\d{0,2})?'))` (without the end matching pattern `$`)

## Steps to Reproduce

1. Input `1111.11`.
2. Move the selection offset to `.1` and the last `1`.
3. Input another number.
4. Move the selection offset after `.1` again.
5. Input another number.

**Actual results:** There can be 6 decimal at most.

**Expected results:** Only 2 decimal allowed.
Labels: a: text input;framework;documentation;has reproducible steps;P4;r: fixed;found in release: 2.1

Title_Description:
Document prod_builders.json and try_builders.json Is there any documentation anywhere that talks about prod_builders.json, what it's schema is, how it's used, where manifest.yaml fits in, and so on? the README in the devicelab directory doesn't seem to mention it, and the files themselves have no comments (and can't have comments, since they're JSON).

It would be great to migrate these to a format (like YAML) that can be self-documenting, and it would be great to have a README (and update the devicelab/README) that explains the context of these files, how to edit them, what the schema is, etc.

Title_Description:
Drawing in Texture() buffer on Windows causes viewport corruption on other widgets in screen <!-- Thank you for using Flutter!

     If you are looking for support, please check out our documentation
     or consider asking a question on Stack Overflow:
      * https://flutter.dev/
      * https://api.flutter.dev/
      * https://stackoverflow.com/questions/tagged/flutter?sort=frequent

     If you have found a bug or if our documentation doesn't have an answer
     to what you're looking for, then fill out the template below. Please read
     our guide to filing a bug first: https://flutter.dev/docs/resources/bug-reports
-->

The Flutter `Texture()` widget on Windows uses the TextureRegistry via native APIs to register a GL backed (pixel buffer?) texture. Although using the buffer itself works perfectly fine, the addition of Texture() into an existing app causes (temporal) draw corruption of the viewports of all non-Texture widgets in the active window (i.e. Text, Icon, and other drawn widgets).

The corrupted viewports seem to be directly linked to the Texture() buffer in question, and it seems to be drawing pixels from the original registered texture in some distorted manner. I haven't dug deep enough yet, but perhaps this GLTexture is being incorrectly re-used in multiple places?

## Steps to Reproduce

<!-- You must include full steps to reproduce so that we can reproduce the problem. -->

1. `git clone https://github.com/lsegal/flutter_windows_texture_bug`
2. `cd flutter_windows_texture_bug/example`
3. `flutter run -d windows`
4. Viewport corruption of Icon widgets should be immediate on window redraw (though it is temporal).
5. Resize the window down to see full corruption of all widgets, including Text().

Note: this project is based on a `flutter create -t plugin` template for the Windows platform. The project needs to run from the `example` directory due to the native plugin registration that happens, though this should not be relevant to the bug itself. The main files that were modified are listed below:

1. `windows/gldraw_plugin.cpp` - contains minimal repro TextureRegistry registration calls with TextureVariant implementation.
2. `lib/gldraw.dart` - contains MethodChannel invocations to plugin.
3. `example/lib/main.dart` - contains a the main app displaying a few Icon, Text and Texture widgets in the same viewport. This is the file to run.

**Expected results:** <!-- what did you want to see? -->

Expecting all Text and Icon widgets to draw correctly:

![image](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/lsegal/flutter_windows_texture_bug/main/assets/expected.png)

**Actual results:** <!-- what did you see? -->

Visible temporal corruption of non-Texture widgets in viewport:

![image](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/lsegal/flutter_windows_texture_bug/main/assets/actual.png)

Title_Description:
Fix and re-enable SkpWarmup tests on Fuchsia Emulator I disabled the tests
```
flutter_runner_tests 
  EngineTest.SkpWarmup
shell_tests
  SkpWarmupTest.Basic
  SkpWarmupTest.Image
```

on Fuchsia Emulator. To see the test fail, you can remove the test filters at
https://flutter.googlesource.com/recipes/+/refs/heads/master/recipes/femu_test.py#206

Then run the femu builder
```
led get-builder 'luci.flutter.try:Linux Fuchsia' | led edit -r femu_test | led edit-recipe-bundle | led launch
```

Title_Description:
TextButton has no content padding in web and desktop unlike mobile As we know TextButton is a replacement to FlatButton. FlatButton content padding is consistent on all platforms. Reproducing this issue is easy just create a TextButton with text inside it and compare the padding in the platforms you will see no content padding in web and desktop only in mobile.

I use:
Flutter 2.0.2
Dart 2.12.1
Windows 10

Thanks!

Title_Description:
Implement better string <-> number conversion functions Right now in a11y we have a very rudimentary StringUtils collection that contains a number of methods such as `NumberToString`.

These need to be made a little bit better by:

- Formatting strings more appropriately when converting from numbers. e.g. `(int)6` becomes `"6.000000"` right now, but it should be `"6"`.
- Implementing `StringToInt` etc that do a better job (e.g. by correctly signalling errors, which `std::stoi` doesn't do) and using them where we would need to validate that the input string can actually be represented as a number.
Labels: engine;a: accessibility;passed first triage;P4
Creator: gw280

Title_Description:
Documentation missing for FFI use with oss code on Linux & Windows Currently on Flutter.dev we have [excellent documentation on how to build a a Flutter plugin that needs to include both C and Dart for use via FFI](https://flutter.dev/docs/development/platform-integration/c-interop#open-source-third-party-library), including the advice to:

> Do not upload this plugin (or any plugin containing binary code) to pub.dev. Instead, this plugin should be downloaded from a trusted third-party, as shown in the CocoaPods example.

But there is no such documentation on how to do this for Linux or Windows platforms.

My usecase is that I want to publish a plugin that provides access via FFI to each desktop platforms audio libaries via [miniaudio](https://github.com/mackron/miniaudio), which is an open source "wrapper library" distributed as single C header file (or single C file & header) so I don't know what the recommended approach is for Linux and Windows?

cc @domesticmouse
Labels: platform-windows;d: api docs;platform-linux;a: desktop;documentation;passed first triage;P4
Creator: maks

Title_Description:
[WEB] Losing url state after hot restart 
<!-- You must include full steps to reproduce so that we can reproduce the problem. -->

1. Run my example app.
2. Got to page two and hot reload.

**Expected results:** Current page reloads, as it used to.

**Actual results:** App reloads and takes you back to the initial route


``` dart

import 'package:flutter/material.dart';

void main() => runApp(const MyApp());

class MyApp extends StatelessWidget {
  const MyApp() : super(key: const ValueKey('MyApp'));

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return MaterialApp(
      initialRoute: '/',
      routes: {
        '/': (context) => MyHomePage(),
        '/second': (context) => MySecondPage(),
      },
    );
  }
}

class MyHomePage extends StatelessWidget {
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) => Scaffold(
        body: Center(
            child: Column(
          children: [
            Text('Home'),
            ElevatedButton(
              onPressed: () => Navigator.of(context).pushNamed('/second'),
              child: Text('Page 2'),
            )
          ],
        )),
      );
}

class MySecondPage extends StatelessWidget {
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) => Scaffold(
        body: Center(child: Text('Page 2')),
      );
}


```

Title_Description:
Keyboard shortcuts stop working when caps lock is down. ### Steps to reproduce 
1. Creat a project on any of the latest channels
2. Add a `TextField()` 
or try the code sample below

<details> 
<summary>code sample</summary> 

```dart
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';

void main() => runApp(MyApp());

class MyApp extends StatelessWidget {
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return MaterialApp(
      title: 'Material App',
      theme: ThemeData.dark(),
      home: Home(),
    );
  }
}

class Home extends StatelessWidget {
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Scaffold(
      appBar: AppBar(
        title: Text('Material App Bar'),
      ),
      body: Center(
        child: TextField(),
      ),
      floatingActionButton: FloatingActionButton(
        child: Icon(Icons.add),
        onPressed: () {},
      ),
    );
  }
}
``` 

</details>

### Actual Results 
Be able to enter only capital text and delete the text with backspace/delete

### Expected Results
Not able to delete text with backspace/delete when text is in caps in the end


Note:
1. If you enter lower caps text right after all caps text, you will be able to delete text backspace/delete
2. If you enter only lower caps, there is no issue
3. It reproduces all channels (check multiple doctor -v below) on the macOS Desktop app

Title_Description:
[macos] [metal] Memory leak when using external texture It looks like there is a huge memory leak when using external texture on macOS. The memory usage of the video_player plugin grows quickly to multiple GB. Could also be that I made some mistake of course.

I am still trying to create a more minimalistic reproduction but until then the example of the macOS port of the video_player plugin can be used to reproduce the issue:
https://github.com/cbenhagen/plugins/tree/video_player_macos_new/packages/video_player/video_player_macos/example

The relevant code returning the buffer is a copy of the iOS implementation:

```objc
- (CVPixelBufferRef)copyPixelBuffer {
  CMTime outputItemTime = [_videoOutput itemTimeForHostTime:CACurrentMediaTime()];
  if ([_videoOutput hasNewPixelBufferForItemTime:outputItemTime]) {
    return [_videoOutput copyPixelBufferForItemTime:outputItemTime itemTimeForDisplay:NULL];
  } else {
    return NULL;
  }
}
```

The whole code can be found here:
https://github.com/cbenhagen/plugins/blob/video_player_macos_new/packages/video_player/video_player_macos/macos/Classes/FLTVideoPlayerPlugin.m

/cc @iskakaushik

Title_Description:
onGenerate called multiple times when app is closed with the back button Pushing a deep link `/details/1` makes three calls to `onGenerateRoute` when the app is closed with the back button. It get's called for each segment of the path, so if  the user opens a link like`/details/1`,  onGenerateRoute is called with `settings.name` set to `/`, `/details`, and `/details/1`.

When the app is open, there is only one call to `onGenerateRoute`, `/details/1`.

I've reproduced this on the master and stable channels (2.0.3)

## Steps to Reproduce

1. Create a new Flutter project
2. Paste in the [on_generate_route.dart](https://github.com/flutter/samples/blob/master/navigation_and_routing/lib/navigator/on_generate_route.dart) sample.
3. [Enable deep linking](https://flutter.dev/docs/development/ui/navigation/deep-linking#enable-deep-linking-on-android) 閳 add the following to app/src/main/AndroidManifest.xml

```
            <!-- Deep linking -->
            <meta-data android:name="flutter_deeplinking_enabled" android:value="true" />
            <intent-filter android:autoVerify="true">
                <action android:name="android.intent.action.VIEW" />
                <category android:name="android.intent.category.DEFAULT" />
                <category android:name="android.intent.category.BROWSABLE" />
                <data android:scheme="http" android:host="flutterbooksample.com" />
                <data android:scheme="https" />
            </intent-filter>
```

4. Set a breakpoint on line 21 and run the app in debug mode
5. press the back button to close the app
6. trigger a deep link using the `adb` command:

```
adb shell am start -a android.intent.action.VIEW \
    -c android.intent.category.BROWSABLE \
    -d "http://flutterbooksample.com/details/1"
```

7. Observe that the breakpoint in `onGenerateRoute` is hit 3 times with `/`, `/details` and `/details/1`.
8. Repeat step 5 and 6 again
9. Observe error:

```
NoSuchMethodError: No top-level getter '_registerPlugins' declared.
Receiver: top-level
Tried calling: _registerPlugins
```

## Related issues
- https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/77680

Title_Description:
Handle empty lists in flutter manifest validation Currently when we validate the types of lists in flutter manifests, we assume that a list is always non-empty. However it is possible to create empty yaml lists using the JSON syntax `foo: []`.

The validator should be updated to check if the list is empty and then skip the validation.


https://github.com/flutter/flutter/blob/master/packages/flutter_tools/lib/src/flutter_manifest.dart#L496

@christopherfujino

Title_Description:
[Web] Very slow fetching of 40MB js file in debug mode First sorry to add to a lot of performance related issues, such as #76009.
If this seems to be already covered in a different issue, please close this one.

I am using the [fhir package](https://pub.dev/packages/fhir). It includes a [generated code file with 17K LOC](https://github.com/MayJuun/fhir/blob/main/fhir/lib/r4/special_types/special_types.freezed.dart) which results in ~40MB javascript file in web debug mode.

Title_Description:
[web] RawKeyDownEvent from RawKeyboardListener contains the literal modifier key name as a character ## Steps to Reproduce Given the following snippet: ```dart RawKeyboardListener( focusNode: focusNode, onKey: (value) { if (value is RawKeyDownEvent) { print('character: ${value.character}'); } }, child: Container(), ), ``` This is the printed output for modifier key down strokes: |Modifier Key | macOS
character value | Web
character value | |:----:|:--------:|:----:| |Shift |null|'Shift'| |Control | null|'Control'| |command | null |'Meta'| |option | null |'Alt'| |capslock | null |'CapsLock'| |return | null | 'Enter'| | ArrowDown| null | 'ArrowDown'| ... and so on for the remaining arrows, `backspace`, `escape`, `Tab`,.... (not sure if there's more?). note: `RawKeyUpEvent` for `Web` prints `null` for all the given modifier keys, so the issue is only with `RawKeyDownEvent` **Expected results:** I expect the character value to be `null` for modifier keys. This is problematic when an application wants to ignore all `null` characters without implementing an additional logic to inspect modifier keys. **Actual results:** The literal name of the character is given which does not make sense.
Flutter Doctor ``` Doctor summary (to see all details, run flutter doctor -v): [閴佹彯 Flutter (Channel stable, 2.0.6, on macOS 11.2.3 20D91 darwin-x64, locale en) [閴佹彯 Android toolchain - develop for Android devices (Android SDK version 29.0.2) [閴佹彯 Xcode - develop for iOS and macOS [閴佹彯 Chrome - develop for the web [閴佹彯 Android Studio (version 4.1) [閴佹彯 VS Code (version 1.55.2) [閴佹彯 Connected device (2 available) 閳 No issues found! ```

Title_Description:
Several web plugins missing integration tests The following plugins don't have example directories or integration tests:
 * [x] image_picker_for_web
 * [x] shared_preferences_web
 * [x] video_player_web

I'm making not having integration tests in a plugin that isn't explicitly listed as excluded when running the tests an error, to avoid repeats of the problem where we silently weren't running a bunch of our integration tests, so I'm going to list these as excluded in .cirrus.yaml for now with a reference to this issue.

If any of these genuinely shouldn't have integration tests, we could update the Cirrus script to explain why, but if there's *anything* we could test I would rather we have minimal tests in place (per the OKR of having a framework in place for every kind of test that could potentially be meaningful) than permanently skip them.

Title_Description:
dart sdk roll breaks cocoon via transitive dep `uuid_enhanced` The `validate_ci_yaml` test broke on the engine roll https://github.com/flutter/flutter/pull/82070 because a transitive dependency (`uuid_enhanced`, depended on by `graphql`) extended an `UnmodifiableUint8ListView`, which is no longer permitted by https://dart.googlesource.com/sdk.git/+/3e9cdc56440bded76d8078a2567910236ad6f7b9%5E%21/#F1

https://ci.chromium.org/p/flutter/builders/try/Linux%20validate_ci_config/1769?

```
../../../x/w/.pub-cache/hosted/pub.dartlang.org/uuid_enhanced-3.0.2/lib/uuid.dart:9:7: Error: 'UnmodifiableUint8ListView' is restricted and can't be extended or implemented.
class Uuid extends UnmodifiableUint8ListView {
      ^
```

To clarify, the `validate_ci_yaml` script does not require `graphql`; however, the cocoon service itself DOES, so landing this change would probably would lead to cocoon being unable to build with the latest Flutter. I am not sure why customer_testing did not fail.
Labels: team;dependency: dart;team: infra;passed secondary triage;P4
Creator: christopherfujino

Title_Description:
[web] [flutter 2.0] Certain font sizes render a greyish bar on top of the text on a smaller screen size ## Steps to Reproduce

**Note**: This seems to happen exclusively on mobile browsers (in my case: a Samsung Galaxy S8 running Chrome v90.0.4430.91, Android 9). Was also able to verify this on a Galaxy S21 and an iPhone 12 Pro.

1. Go to https://flutter-text-issue.web.app/ or checkout https://github.com/ricardo-durao-3r/flutter-text-issue and deploy the app so it's accessible on your mobile device (e.g., via ngrok). 
2. Expand the ExpansionTile and see that the left side text of the list item has a greyish bar on top of it while the ones that are simply inside the ListView don't have that greyish bar.
3. Do notice that if the text's font size is increased from 10px to 12px, the issue is gone.

| W/O Expansion Tile | With Expansion Tile |
|----------------------------|----------------------------|
| ![Screenshot_20210510-114328_Chrome](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/74183351/117660537-30172a00-b195-11eb-8142-c08a7181d848.jpg) | ![Screenshot_20210510-114337_Chrome](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/74183351/117660547-32798400-b195-11eb-9c66-880c5e79c1ed.jpg) |

**Expected results:** texts that are children of expansion tiles should not suffer unexpected changes, regardless of their font sizes.

**Actual results:** the text on the left side has a greyish bar on top of it when the font size is 10px

Title_Description:
Missing artifact dependency in UWP build? I haven't tried to reproduce this, and don't have time to dig into the tool internals at the moment, but I wanted to capture this for investigation. I just tried to a do a UWP build on my Windows machine, which hadn't been updated in a little while, and did the following:
- Updated my Flutter tree to the latest master
- Ran `flutter create --platforms=winuwp .` to add a winuwp folder to a plugin's example directory
- Ran `flutter build winuwp`

My build failed due to a missing identifier: `FlutterDesktopViewControllerCreateFromCoreWindow` when compiling flutter_view_controller.cc (in the wrapper). My tree is new enough that the PR that replaced that symbol has rolled in, so the fact that it's missing is expected, but flutter_view_controller.cc shouldn't have had a reference to it.

I tried:
- `flutter precache`
- `flutter build winuwp`

and the error was gone. That makes me think that the UWP build is missing a dependency internally on the client wrapper artifact, since otherwise it should have been fetched on demand.

(I suspect the STR here would be something like: check out an older tree, wipe the artifact cache, build for Win32, update tree to latest, build for UWP.)

/cc @cbracken @jonahwilliams
Labels: tool;platform-windows;a: desktop;a: build;P4
Creator: stuartmorgan

Title_Description:
(DiffContext) ImageFilterLayer should not contribute to readback region Currently the ImageFilterLayer will register its bounds as a readback layer in the DiffContext. This could potentially expand the dirty regions of some nearby layers. After a long discussion with @knopp we believe that this extra readback region processing is not necessary for ImageFilterLayer so the registration of the readback region should be removed.

See https://github.com/flutter/engine/blob/221623d2bb9798411c170d92d69009e0d3b4d435/flow/layers/image_filter_layer.cc#L44

Title_Description:
Retry chrome launch on debug connection failure web_tool_tests flake on setting up the debug connection with chrome:

https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/flutter/builders/prod/Linux%20web_tool_tests/2305/overview

Not sure if this is the right fix, but when hitting the exception here:

https://github.com/flutter/flutter/blob/59cdad49143c967cef2d46ae510a24c00d2b6f71/packages/flutter_tools/lib/src/web/chrome.dart#L392

instead of throwing a tool exit, we might try killing chrome and trying again some number of times. There's already a retry loop for spawning chrome, so maybe it just needs to be a bit wider to encompass the connection check as well?

/cc @jonahwilliams @grouma @annagrin

Title_Description:
effectiveConstraints is buggy.  I added a visual density to my app, and now I get:

BoxConstraints has both width and height constraints non-normalized

The problem is I'm setting a BoxContraint to 32,32 (min/max for width and height) on an IconButton

But internally it calls effectiveContraints and changes the minWidth, but it doesn't set the maxWidth.

After this call, I have a boxContraint that is minWidth: 44 and maxWidth: 32 and this triggers the crash.

I'm on Flutter web if that matters, but I assume it would happen everywhere.
```dart
/// Return a copy of [constraints] whose minimum width and height have been
  /// updated with the [baseSizeAdjustment].
  BoxConstraints effectiveConstraints(BoxConstraints constraints){
    assert(constraints != null && constraints.debugAssertIsValid());
    return constraints.copyWith(
      minWidth: (constraints.minWidth + baseSizeAdjustment.dx).clamp(0.0, double.infinity).toDouble(),
      minHeight: (constraints.minHeight + baseSizeAdjustment.dy).clamp(0.0, double.infinity).toDouble(),
    );
  }
```
I'm doing this:
```dart
  IconButton(
      constraints: BoxConstraints.tight(const Size(32, 32)),
    ...
```
And I added this for the visualDensity to my app
```dart 
      ThemeData(visualDensity: Utils.isWeb
          ? const VisualDensity(horizontal: 3, vertical: 3)
          : VisualDensity.adaptivePlatformDensity,
```

Title_Description:
Illegal use of properties in engine.py recipe When using properties in recipes, we seem to use `api.properties.get` in the `RunSteps` branch of the code, this is deprecated, and isn't working well in our tests, see: https://flutter.googlesource.com/recipes/+/refs/heads/master/recipes/engine.py#1675.

This boils down to the fact the protobuf3 doesn't support wrapped primitive values and results in problems where

`api.properties.get('some_property_key', True)` to always return true even when `some_property_key` is explicitly set to `false`. This causes our `GenTests` code to generate code ignoring the branches that evaluate to `False`.
Labels: team: infra;passed secondary triage;P4;tech-debt
Creator: iskakaushik

Title_Description:
flutter/plugins 'release' step generates too much output when waiting This is an example run where the `release` step timed out waiting for all the other tests to succeed:
https://github.com/flutter/plugins/runs/2893964067
Loading that page in Chrome results in a "do you want to kill this hanging page" dialog because there's so much output that the GitHub UI can't really handle it.

We should dial down the amount of output we print during that step (including by polling less often)

Title_Description:
[web] autofillHints on TextFormField causes soft keyboard in iOS browsers to re-appear unexpectedly ## Steps to Reproduce Code for minimal flutter web example available here: https://github.com/fearlessambassador/flutter_text_field_issue. Deployed app can be accessed here: https://flutter-text-field-issue.web.app Please note that this occurs on mobile browsers. I use Chrome browser on an iPhone. Please note that this problem does NOT occur on **stable channel**, but I can reproduce across **master, dev and beta** channels. 1. Open https://flutter-text-field-issue.web.app and click button "Go to text field" 2. Enter the text field 3. At this point the keyboard will reappear unexpectedly even when unfocused or navigating back to the Home page (ie. even after the widget has been disposed of) **Fixing the issue** The issue can be fixed by removing the "autofillHints: const [AutofillHints.email]" on the TextFieldPage-widget. Once removed this issue no longer appears. However, it is important to be able to use the AutofillHints behavior. **Expected results:** That the keyboard remains deactivated when NOT interacting with a TextFormField **Actual results:** The virtual keyboard on re-appears when interacting with the app, even though the TextFormField's parent widget has been disposed of. For example, after navigating back to the Home page which does not contain a TextFormField the virtual keyboard will re-appear, see below screenshot. After dismissing it, it will re-appear on new interactions with the app.

     using profile or release mode. Verify that the performance issue can be

     Does the problem occur on an emulator/simulator as well as on physical devices?
-->

**Target Platform: macOS**
**Target OS version/browser: Big sur 11.4 (20F71)**
**Devices: MacBook Pro (16-inch, 2019)**

A simple flutter application (which only contains a `TextField` widget), but it takes up **10%** of the CPU.

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/17426470/124296463-906e8a80-db8c-11eb-99c6-db13e27f2bab.png)

## Reproduce

1. copy this code to your example project `main.dart`.
```dart
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';

void main() {
  runApp(const MyApp());
}

class MyApp extends StatelessWidget {
  const MyApp({Key? key}) : super(key: key);

  // This widget is the root of your application.
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return MaterialApp(
      title: 'Flutter Demo',
      theme: ThemeData(
        primarySwatch: Colors.blue,
      ),
      home: const Scaffold(
        body: TextField(autofocus: true),
      ),
    );
  }
}

```

2. `flutter run -d macos --profile`

3.  We could use command top to check our flutter_app CPU usage: ```top -pid `pgrep flutter_app` ```

Title_Description:
[google_maps_flutter_web] The google maps widget doesn't behave as the mobile version (polyline) I'm currently working on a Flutter application mobile/web and I have an issue with the "google_maps_flutter" package. My goal is to display a map with a course drawn thanks to a polyline.

Here is a screenshot of the Android version which is working as expected :

![Screenshot_20210713_153909_dev doarun app](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/54772403/125461863-330ea22e-5c0d-4e18-9b2b-1a7246d02835.jpg)

Now, we have the web version which displays the Polyline as a straight line heading to the north :

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/54772403/125462520-4d5f0c46-6efc-489d-9ac2-13d2af6ef5b4.png)

Here is the code sample of my `GoogleMap` widget :

```
GoogleMap(
                  gestureRecognizers: Set()
                    ..add(Factory<PanGestureRecognizer>(
                        () => PanGestureRecognizer())),
                  initialCameraPosition: CameraPosition(
                      target: polylines.first.points.first, zoom: 20.0),
                  mapType: MapType.hybrid,
                  polylines: polylines,
                  compassEnabled: false,
                  tiltGesturesEnabled: false),
            ),
```

Title_Description:
Empty example folder in the root of the app prevents from generating plugin registration <!-- Thank you for using Flutter!

     If you are looking for support, please check out our documentation
     or consider asking a question on Stack Overflow:
      * https://flutter.dev/
      * https://api.flutter.dev/
      * https://stackoverflow.com/questions/tagged/flutter?sort=frequent

     If you have found a bug or if our documentation doesn't have an answer
     to what you're looking for, then fill out the template below. Please read
     our guide to filing a bug first: https://flutter.dev/docs/resources/bug-reports
-->

## Steps to Reproduce

<!-- You must include full steps to reproduce so that we can reproduce the problem. -->

1. Run `flutter create bug`.
2. Create an empty folder called example in the new flutter project
3. Run `flutter pub add  shared_preferences` (or any plugin that creates an Android Module)
4. Run `flutter pub get` 

**Expected results:** <!-- what did you want to see? -->
Flutter generates all needed files, including GeneratedPluginRegistrant.java and the application can start/compile run. 

**Actual results:** <!-- what did you see? -->
Flutter doesn't generate the file or warn you, the verbose output of flutter pub get shows no error and skips the Found plugin section completely.  The application fails, the Android plugins are not loaded. 

This happens on Linux and Windows (had no time to check Mac), it took me 1.5 Day to find this (and a complete reinstallation of my OS as I first thought I broke something). From my point of view this can (and did for me) lead to a long-running search for the actual cause, if possible one of the tools should at least print an error that it failed/stopped.

Title_Description:
[linux] In a multiline TextField HOME and END keys do not jump from start to end of line <!-- Thank you for using Flutter!

     If you are looking for support, please check out our documentation
     or consider asking a question on Stack Overflow:

     to what you're looking for, then fill out the template below. Please read
     our guide to filing a bug first: https://flutter.dev/docs/resources/bug-reports
-->
## Description
When using home and end in multiline textfield the cursor moves from beginning of the document to the end of the document, instead of the beginning of the line to the end of the line.

## Steps to Reproduce
<!-- You must include full steps to reproduce so that we can reproduce the problem. -->

1. Create flutter app with a multiline textfield on platform linux:


<details> 
<summary>minimal code sample</summary> 

```dart
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';

void main() => runApp(MyApp());

class MyApp extends StatelessWidget {
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return MaterialApp(
      title: 'Text Edit',
      home: _TextFieldExample(),
    );
  }
}

class _TextFieldExample extends StatefulWidget {
  @override
  _TextFieldExampleState createState() => _TextFieldExampleState();
}

class _TextFieldExampleState extends State<_TextFieldExample> {
  final FocusNode _focusNode = FocusNode();
  final TextEditingController _textController = TextEditingController();

  @override
  void dispose() {
    _focusNode.dispose();
    _textController.dispose();
    super.dispose();
  }

  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Scaffold(
      appBar: AppBar(
        title: Text('Text Test'),
      ),
      body: Center(
        child: Column(
          mainAxisAlignment: MainAxisAlignment.center,
          children: [
            SizedBox(
              width: 400,
              child: TextField(
                controller: _textController,
                focusNode: _focusNode,
                maxLines: 10,
                keyboardType: TextInputType.multiline,
                decoration: InputDecoration(
                  hintText: 'Write something, then press HOME and END key',
                  border: const OutlineInputBorder(),
                ),
              ),
            ),
          ],
        ),
      ),
    );
  }
}
``` 

</details>

2. run app
3. enter a couple lines of text
4. press home and enter

**Expected results:** <!-- what did you want to see? -->
cursor moves from beginning of line to end of line (and vice versa)

**Actual results:** <!-- what did you see? -->
cursor moves from beginning of textfield to end of document (and vice versa)

Title_Description:
[Windows][Desktop] Some special characters are duplicated when using keyboard with AltGr Hello,

I wanted to test flutter Desktop a little bit and found two bugs that I also found in the Issues here but marked as closed and not editable anymore, so I wanted to open up a new Issue.

For the Textformfield, there still seems to be a problem with the ctrl + backspace (Block delete) function. Everytime I hit ctrl + backspace, an unknown character (black square like in #78974) presents itself while then deleting a part of the word written before. 

Even worse, when entering an email adress, the @ sign is written twice.. so if I hit AltGr plus Q on my German keyboard, the textformfield shows @@ instead of @. Tried several branches, on stable altgr made my keyboard do weir things, so I switched to master.

Will there be acceptable performance for the textformfield soon? Especially the @ problem makes the use of textformfields pretty impossible and I would say thats a pretty basic widget needed for nearly every app.

Title_Description:
[file_selector_web] Cannot stream chunks from large files (~2gb) ## Steps to Reproduce

**Step 1:**
Run the following code on the web:
Snippet (complete code attached below):
```dart
    final fileSize = await file.length();
    final chunkStarts = List.generate((fileSize/chunkSize.toDouble()).ceil(), (i) => i * chunkSize);

    for (var chunkStart in chunkStarts){
      final bytes = await file.openRead(chunkStart, min(fileSize, chunkStart + chunkSize)).single;
      print("Streamed ${bytes.length} bytes");
    }
```
<details>
 <summary>main.dart</summary>

```dart
import 'dart:math';

import 'package:file_selector/file_selector.dart';
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';

void main() async {
  WidgetsFlutterBinding.ensureInitialized();

  runApp(MaterialApp(home: OpenImagePage()));
}

/// Screen that shows an example of openFiles
class OpenImagePage extends StatelessWidget {
  void _openImageFile(BuildContext context) async {
    final XTypeGroup typeGroup = XTypeGroup(
      label: 'Video files',
      extensions: ['mp4'],
    );
    final XFile file = (await openFile(acceptedTypeGroups: [typeGroup]));
    print(file.name);
    print(file.path);

    print('Will attempt to iterate through stream in chunks');
    final chunkSize = 5000000;
    final fileSize = await file.length();
    print("File size: ${fileSize}");
    final chunkStarts = List.generate((fileSize/chunkSize.toDouble()).ceil(), (i) => i * chunkSize);

    var totalBytesStreamed = 0;
    for (var chunkStart in chunkStarts){
      final chunkEnd = min(fileSize, chunkStart + chunkSize);
      print("Opening chunk [$chunkStart, $chunkEnd]");
      final bytes = await file.openRead(chunkStart, min(fileSize, chunkStart + chunkSize)).single;
      print("Streamed ${bytes.length} bytes");
      totalBytesStreamed += bytes.length;
    }
    print("Total bytes streamed: $totalBytesStreamed");
  }

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Scaffold(
      appBar: AppBar(
        title: const Text("Open video file_selector"),
      ),
      body: Center(
        child: Column(
          mainAxisAlignment: MainAxisAlignment.center,
          children: <Widget>[
            ElevatedButton(
              style: ElevatedButton.styleFrom(
                primary: Colors.blue,
                onPrimary: Colors.white,
              ),
              child: const Text('Press to open a file'),
              onPressed: () => _openImageFile(context),
            ),
          ],
        ),
      ),
    );
  }
}

```
</details>

Open a large file mp4 (`2gb` or larger file)

All chunks can be streamed regardless of file size.

Title_Description:
[Camera] CamcorderProfile deprecated in Android API level 31 The camera plugin can not be used with Android API level 31 because it uses a deprecated method and warnings are treated as errors.

## Steps to Reproduce

1. Start new project and use latest camera plugin
2. Set compile and target API versions in your build.gradle file to API level 31:
```
compileSdkVersion = 31
targetSdkVersion = 31
```
3. `flutter build apk`

**Expected results:** Build is successful

**Actual results:** Build fails with 8 warnings, treated as one error.

```
camera/features/resolution/ResolutionFeature.java:135: warning: [deprecation] get(int,int) in CamcorderProfile has been deprecated
           return CamcorderProfile.get(cameraId, CamcorderProfile.QUALITY_HIGH);
                                  ^
camera/features/resolution/ResolutionFeature.java:139: warning: [deprecation] get(int,int) in CamcorderProfile has been deprecated
           return CamcorderProfile.get(cameraId, CamcorderProfile.QUALITY_2160P);
                                  ^
camera/features/resolution/ResolutionFeature.java:143: warning: [deprecation] get(int,int) in CamcorderProfile has been deprecated
           return CamcorderProfile.get(cameraId, CamcorderProfile.QUALITY_1080P);
                                  ^
camera/features/resolution/ResolutionFeature.java:147: warning: [deprecation] get(int,int) in CamcorderProfile has been deprecated
           return CamcorderProfile.get(cameraId, CamcorderProfile.QUALITY_720P);
                                  ^
camera/features/resolution/ResolutionFeature.java:151: warning: [deprecation] get(int,int) in CamcorderProfile has been deprecated
           return CamcorderProfile.get(cameraId, CamcorderProfile.QUALITY_480P);
                                  ^
camera/features/resolution/ResolutionFeature.java:155: warning: [deprecation] get(int,int) in CamcorderProfile has been deprecated
           return CamcorderProfile.get(cameraId, CamcorderProfile.QUALITY_QVGA);
                                  ^
camera/features/resolution/ResolutionFeature.java:159: warning: [deprecation] get(int,int) in CamcorderProfile has been deprecated
           return CamcorderProfile.get(cameraId, CamcorderProfile.QUALITY_LOW);
                                  ^
 error: warnings found and -Werror specified
camera/media/MediaRecorderBuilder.java:15: warning: [deprecation] MediaRecorder() in MediaRecorder has been deprecated
       return new MediaRecorder();
              ^
 1 error
 8 warnings
```

This affects https://github.com/flutter/flutter/pull/89511 which relands https://github.com/flutter/engine/pull/24756 which requires Android API 31. 

@blasten I'm pinging you here since you are most familiar with the affected issues and you also seem to have solved this in the past, when the camera did not work with API 30 https://github.com/flutter/plugins/pull/3299 - I intend to also open a PR for this issue, but I still think you should be in the loop.

Title_Description:
[macOS][desktop] keyboard Input doesn't work anymore when entering text during hot restart ### Description
So I was trying to reproduce https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/89729. That issue throws ` KeyUpEvent is dispatched, but the state shows that the physical key is not pressed.` and followed by a bunch of other exceptions but the key issue (no pun intended) is that when we `hot restart` and enter text, the keyboard input stops working and the errors are thrown. 

Now coming to macOS, not only are error messages different than Linux but the main difference is how it reproduces, simply a hot restart is not enough, the issue gets introduced when you try to enter text during `hot restart` before the hot restart is finished processing. if we `hot restart`, let it complete, the error is not introduced, while Linux desktop keyboard input stops working even if you wait after the hot restart, and of course, error messages are different than macOS.

### `macOS` (first hot restart and wait for `hot restart` to finish then enter text -> no issue)


https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/48603081/132688729-d24c00c8-a608-42a6-b8aa-d486ef539cf0.mov


### `macOS` (first hot restart and quickly try to enter text before `hot restart` is completed (repeat it few times)-> issues gets introduced and input stops working)



https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/48603081/132689808-27ffa8ab-66a8-4937-b9bf-620f8662ab28.mov




### Reproducible code sample

<details> 
<summary>complete minimal runnable code sample</summary>

```dart
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';

void main() => runApp(MyApp());

class MyApp extends StatelessWidget {
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return MaterialApp(
      title: 'Material App',
      theme: ThemeData.dark(),
      home: Home(),
    );
  }
}

class Home extends StatelessWidget {
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Scaffold(
      appBar: AppBar(
        title: Text('Material App Bar'),
      ),
      body: Center(
        child: TextField(
        ),
      ),
      floatingActionButton: FloatingActionButton(
        child: Icon(Icons.add),
        onPressed: () {},
      ),
    );
  }
}
``` 

</details>

Title_Description:
[Android] Streamline Edge-to-Edge and Navigation Bar behavior across Android versions ## Background
https://github.com/flutter/flutter/pull/81303 added support for the Edge to Edge fullscreen mode introduced in Android 10 (SDK 29).
https://github.com/flutter/engine/pull/28616 limited the support for Edge to Edge to Android 10 (SDK 29) and higher.

In the following, "Android 10+" will refer to "Android 10 (SDK 29) and upwards".

## Expectations

The guidelines over at https://developer.android.com/training/gestures/edge-to-edge show the following:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/6409465/133358665-43872d0e-4e0e-40e7-8f3b-b63d1c3c753c.png)
With Android 10+, apps should basically always set a transparent navigation bar color.
Setting a ``SystemUiOverlayStyle`` in Flutter with ``systemNavigationBarColor: Colors.transparent`` and ``systemNavigationBarContrastEnforced: true`` (the enforced contrast already defaults to on) enables Android 10+ to (dynamically) show a scrim behind the navigation bar to make the buttons clearly visible. This can be seen on the left image.

When the user chooses gesture navigations, it's expected that apps do not show a a color/overlay behind the bar. This can be seen on the right image. (This is automatically done by Android.)

In both images, the transparent navigation bar color takes effect. In the first image, the white scrim is created by Android (as the transparent navigation bar color possibly couldn't provide enough contrast). In the second image (with gesture navigation), no overlay is shown (as the transparent navigation bar color fully takes effect and no overlay is needed with only the "gesture bar").

## Reality

Currently, Flutter apps do the following by default:
(Taken from: flutter/gallery#643)
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/6409465/133359040-7cf19534-8188-4afc-bb0b-14cf43c854bf.png)
This looks especially weird on devices with rounded corners when the user has gesture navigations on.

### SDK >= 29

Here, ``darkMode`` defines if the user has currently selected a dark theme. 
```dart
SystemChrome.setEnabledSystemUIMode(SystemUiMode.edgeToEdge); // Enable Edge-to-Edge on Android 10+
SystemChrome.setSystemUIOverlayStyle(SystemUiOverlayStyle(
  systemNavigationBarColor: Colors.transparent, // Setting a transparent navigation bar color
  systemNavigationBarContrastEnforced: true, // Default
  systemNavigationBarIconBrightness: darkMode ? Brightness.light : Brightness.dark, // This defines the color of the scrim
));
```
When this is called on Android 10+, the behavior is perfect and as expected:
- Navigation Bar: transparent scrim is shown
- Gesture Navigations: no scrim or other overlay is shown -> fully transparent navigation bar

However, when this is called on Android versions below 10 (below SDK 29), the following happens:
While the Edge-to-Edge fullscreen mode will be ignored because of https://github.com/flutter/engine/pull/28616, it still causes the following issues:
- SDK 26-28: The typical white on black navigation bar is shown. However, in these SDK versions, it's possible to set the navigation bar color with Flutter. So, if a light theme is applied, a white navigation bar with dark navigation bar icons should be shown (and the other way around).
- SDK 19-25: The typical white on black navigation bar is shown. This is fine.

### SDK < 29
For everything older than Android 10 (below SDK 29), the following code produces the expected behavior:
Here, ``darkMode`` defines if the user has currently selected a dark theme. 
```dart
SystemChrome.setSystemUIOverlayStyle(SystemUiOverlayStyle(
  systemNavigationBarColor: darkMode ? Colors.black : Colors.white,
  systemNavigationBarIconBrightness: darkMode ? Brightness.light : Brightness.dark,
));
```
Like expected, if a light theme is shown, the user sees a white navigation bar with dark buttons (and the other way around).
For Android 10+, the user gets the weird "navigation bar overlay" even when using gesture navigations (because edge-to-edge is not enabled). (-> the current "default" behavior in Flutter)

### Combining?

One could make the assumption that the code can be combined without doing any Android version checking in Dart:

```dart
SystemChrome.setEnabledSystemUIMode(SystemUiMode.edgeToEdge); // Enable Edge-to-Edge on Android 10+
SystemChrome.setSystemUIOverlayStyle(SystemUiOverlayStyle(
  systemNavigationBarColor: Colors.transparent, // Setting a transparent navigation bar color
  systemNavigationBarContrastEnforced: true, // Default
  systemNavigationBarIconBrightness: darkMode ? Brightness.light : Brightness.dark, // This defines the color of the scrim
));
```

However, this causes issues on everything older than Android 10 (below SDK 29):
- SDK 26-28: Because the transparent navigation bar is still set, it will show a completely black navigation bar with black navigation bar buttons (which are completely invisible) if light mode is selected. This is behavior that needs to be fixed.
- SDK 19-25: The typical white on black navigation bar is shown. This is fine.

### Correct Usage

The following code should produce expected behavior on all Android verisons.
```dart
Future<void> redoSystemStyle(bool darkMode) async {
  if (Platform.isAndroid) {
    final AndroidDeviceInfo androidInfo = await deviceInfoPlugin.androidInfo;
    final bool edgeToEdge = androidInfo.version.sdkInt != null && androidInfo.version.sdkInt! >= 29;

    // The commented out check below isn't required anymore since https://github.com/flutter/engine/pull/28616 is merged
    // if (edgeToEdge)
    SystemChrome.setEnabledSystemUIMode(SystemUiMode.edgeToEdge);

    SystemChrome.setSystemUIOverlayStyle(SystemUiOverlayStyle(
      statusBarColor: Colors.transparent, // Not relevant to this issue
      systemNavigationBarColor: edgeToEdge
          ? Colors.transparent
          : darkMode
              ? Colors.black
              : Colors.white,
      systemNavigationBarContrastEnforced: true,
      systemNavigationBarIconBrightness: darkMode ? Brightness.light : Brightness.dark,
    ));
  } else {
    SystemChrome.setSystemUIOverlayStyle(const SystemUiOverlayStyle(
      statusBarColor: Colors.transparent, // Not relevant to this issue
    ));
  }
```
Caveats:
- DeviceInfoPlugin required for checking Android version -> makes this "easy task" kind of complicated
- DeviceInfoPlugin call is asynchronous and will cause a brief flash (of the navigation bar) when starting the app:
   This can be avoided by calling ``if (Platform.isAndroid) await deviceInfoPlugin.androidInfo;`` in ``main.dart`` (before "starting the app") on a globally defined DeviceInfoPlugin instance:
``final DeviceInfoPlugin deviceInfoPlugin = DeviceInfoPlugin();``, as the plugin caches these results in the instance

## Use case

Make it easier for users to implement the new Edge-to-Edge fullscreen behavior in Android 10 and onwards while maintaining proper (navigation bar) behavior on older SDK versions without much effort.
Basically, it shouldn't be required to check the Android SDK version in Dart logic for the expected/default Android 10+ behavior (and not break on older Android versions).

## Proposal

There are different possibilities to solve this issue:
- let enabling ``SystemUiMode.edgeToEdge`` always set the navigation bar color to transparent
   -> This seems like the easiest solution but it could potentially confuse users as to why their custom ``systemNavigationBarColor`` is ignored on Android 10+. (Although I do not see a use-case where you could ever want that?)
   Currently, some users are confused that enabling the edge-to-edge mode requires a transparent navigation bar color in order to do anything really. I'd assume that because of the few people using edge-to-edge behavior in Flutter at the moment, this change might be feasible. (``stable`` branch still activates it for more SDK versions) (also, nobody sets a custom navigation bar color when wanting to use proper edge-to-edge behavior?)
- make an (official) Flutter package which can take of Android edge-to-edge/navigation bar handling
   -> This seems too complicated for a "simple styling issue".
- introduce another method (or modify the existing methods?) in ``SystemChrome`` to handle this
   -> This is worded very openly and could mean anything
   -> Perhaps introduce a fallback navigation bar color (black/white for older Android versions) but still require to explicitly set the transparent navigation bar color for Android 10+?
- ...?

## Notes
Maintainers, feel free to edit/update this issue with with your ideas.
To everyone else, I'll try to update this issue with your ideas/feedback to collect the "main ideas".

cc @Piinks
Labels: new feature;platform-android;framework;proposal;passed first triage;P4
Creator: TheJulianJES

Title_Description:
TransformLayer should participate in raster caching The framework uses `RepaintBoundary`s to push `OffsetLayer`s to signify an area that should paint independently. This gets turned into a `TransformLayer` on the engine side, with an `SkMatrix` that is translate-only.

This may result in multiple pictures that are individually raster cached, but often times a repaint boundary indicates an entire area of multiple pictures that would benefit from raster caching. This is particularly true in scrolling use cases, where repaint boundaries are used to animate the offset of a layer.

It should be possible for `flutter::TransformLayer`s to check if they are a translation only matrix and raster cache using the same heuristics as other layers today. The theory is that this will help with scrolling scenarios. We'll want to monitor impact on memory usage.

/cc @goderbauer @flar

Title_Description:
RasterCache should consolidate the caches Right now we create separate cache maps for each type of item that we cache - SkPictures, DisplayLists, and flutter::Layers. The need for multiple caches is to simplify the map keys which are just the individual IDs that each of these objects provides.

Since the IDs are in separate domains (i.e. any of the 3 can have an instance with an ID of, say, 5) we cannot use them as the hash if we mix them in the same map. To mix them we'll have to come up with a more complicated hash that combines their IDs with a type to avoid cache collisions.
Labels: team;engine;passed first triage;P4;tech-debt
Creator: flar

**Actual behaviour:** IME briefly flashes "A" (current input mode, unchanged). Task bar icon does not switch from A to 閵. Subsequent typing remains in romaji (latin) input mode.

Title_Description:
[Proposal][video_player][web] Provide a way to reliably check whether or not a video has buffered enough to play video consistently ## Use case
On web, using `video_player`, if I start a video and wait for it to be buffered to start playing, it often results as it doesn't have enough data and falls back in buffering mode again. It all depends on the connection speed indeed but this makes playing unpredictable.

## Proposal
The latest version of `video_player` plugin sets buffering as `false` as soon as `onCanPlay` is called. To make the behavior more predictable, only the `onCanPlayThrough` should set it to `false`, as we can be sure that we have enough data to actually play the video, uninterrupted.

Another idea could be to have different status or at least some way of knowing if it is really buffered enough (onCanPlayThrough).

In the end, the important part for us is to be able to differentiate the buffer state and be able to tell if playing the video is actually doable.
Labels: plugin;p: first party;platform-web;p: video_player;proposal;passed first triage;passed secondary triage;assigned for triage;P4;r: fixed

Title_Description:
Cannot flutter create when offline # Without flag 

## Repro steps

1. Download a stable macOS build from the releases page: https://docs.flutter.dev/development/tools/sdk/releases

2. Go offline (turn off wifi and anyther other network connection)

3. Extract the downloaded zip (e.g. ~/tmp/flutter)

4. Open a terminal, and run `~/tmp/flutter/bin/flutter create app1`

## Actual result

The command hangs:

```
mit-macbookpro4:tmp mit$ ./flutter/bin/flutter create app2
Running "flutter pub get" in flutter_tools...                          鐚
```

If you run it with verbose, you can see it's failing trying to get to pub:
https://gist.github.com/mit-mit/17d8f6c21f8970fb6b9dba9e0f24c4cb

## Expected result

The command doesn't hang. We should probably detect that we're offline and pass the --offline flag? Looks like that might be tracked in https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/15717

# With flag 

## Repro steps

1. Download a stable macOS build from the releases page: https://docs.flutter.dev/development/tools/sdk/releases

2. Go offline (turn off wifi and anyther other network connection)

3. Extract the downloaded zip (e.g. ~/tmp/flutter)

4. Open a terminal, and run `~/tmp/flutter/bin/flutter create --offline app1`

## Actual result

The command fails trying to download some pub packages ([full log file](https://gist.github.com/mit-mit/5839997c24d6feba0174f36f095d0ba6)):

```
mit-macbookpro4:tmp mit$ ./flutter/bin/flutter --verbose create --offline foobar
...
[ +105 ms] MSG : Resolving dependencies...
[  +76 ms] SLVR: fact: flutter_tools is 0.0.0
...
[ +175 ms] MSG : Resolving dependencies...
...
[        ] SLVR: fact: flutter_tools depends on test 1.17.12
...
[  +13 ms] IO  : Get versions from https://pub.dartlang.org/api/packages/test.
[  +18 ms] IO  : HTTP GET https://pub.dartlang.org/api/packages/test
[        ]     | Accept: application/vnd.pub.v2+json
[        ]     | X-Pub-OS: macos
[        ]     | X-Pub-Command: get
[        ]     | X-Pub-Session-ID: DDBCDF1B-745B-4417-B0A9-ABE58D1EF131
[        ]     | X-Pub-Environment: flutter_cli:get
[        ]     | user-agent: Dart pub 2.15.1
[  +91 ms] IO  : HTTP error:
[        ]     | SocketException: Failed host lookup: 'pub.dartlang.org' (OS Error: nodename nor servname provided, or not known, errno = 8)

```

## Expected result

The command doesn't hang. 

Are the dependencies of the flutter tool not expected to be pre-populated into the cache? It looks like it doesn't have test 1.17.2:

```
mit-macbookpro4:pub.dartlang.org mit$ pwd
/Users/mit/tmp/flutter/.pub-cache/hosted/pub.dartlang.org

mit-macbookpro4:pub.dartlang.org mit$ ls -l | grep test
drwx------@  7 mit  primarygroup  224 Dec 16 20:31 file_testing-3.0.0
drwx------@ 14 mit  primarygroup  448 Dec 16 20:31 test-1.17.12
drwx------@ 10 mit  primarygroup  320 Dec 16 20:31 test_api-0.4.3
drwx------@  8 mit  primarygroup  256 Dec 16 20:31 test_core-0.4.2
```

## Proposal

Before checking if there is an `AndroidManifest.xml` in an `android` directory and if that directory exists, check if the working directory **is a Flutter project**.  

### Steps

1. Check if the current working directory is a Flutter project 閳 check for a `pubspec.yaml` file.
2. Check if there is an `android` directory.
3. Check for the `AndroidManifest.xml` file.

Currently, step 2. is missing.

Title_Description:
[Android] App crashes after moving the app to background Hello, we have a major regression with latest Flutter 2.8+ and HybridViews in Android < 10.

using  `await PlatformViewsService.synchronizeToNativeViewHierarchy(false);` every action that makes the app go to background (for example clicking the ad, or sharing some content) makes the app crash.

Removing the line or Downgrading flutter seems to fix the issue but i consider this a major regression considering it was introduced by Flutter 2.8+ and it is now the recommended way of having inline ads on older devices..

Here is the example app, just run it on Old Android and click the button or the Example banner.

https://github.com/atrope/my_app

I'm facing a weird behaviour in my flutter test. I have a list of 6 elements, and I'm trying to test the drag and drop of the 2nd element after the 4th one.
I can't manage to do it and it looks like it can only be dropped after the 3rd element or the 5th one.

The code sample provided is a  test that tries to drag the 2nd element of the list just after the 4th one.

Note the `extra` value which I changed between runs to drag a little bit further down the 2nd element.

## Steps to Reproduce

<!-- Please include full steps to reproduce so that we can reproduce the problem. -->

1. Execute `flutter test` on the code sample (see "Code sample" section below).
The test fails because the element is actually dragged after the 3rd element instead of the 4th one.

**Expected results:** <!-- what did you want to see? -->

It should be able to drag the 2nd element after the 4th one in the test.

**Actual results:** <!-- what did you see? -->

<details>
<summary>Code sample</summary>

<!--
      Please create a minimal reproducible sample that shows the problem
      and attach it below between the lines with the backticks.

      To create it you can use `flutter create bug` command and update the `main.dart` file.

      Alternatively, you can use https://dartpad.dev/
      which is capable of creating and running small Flutter apps.

      Without this we will unlikely be able to progress on the issue, and because of that
      we regretfully will have to close it.
-->

```dart
void main() {
  testWidgets('It should drag the 2nd element after the 4th one', (WidgetTester tester) async {
    const int itemCount = 6;
    final List<int> items = List<int>.generate(itemCount, (int index) => index);
    const double height = 50; // Height of the elements in the list.
    const double margin = 2; // Element margin so they are visible in the golden images.

    const double extra = 0; // Extra `dy` offset the 2nd element will be dragged.

    void handleReorder(int fromIndex, int toIndex) {
      if (toIndex > fromIndex) {
        toIndex -= 1;
      }
      items.insert(toIndex, items.removeAt(fromIndex));
    }

    final widget = MaterialApp(
      home: Scaffold(
        body: ReorderableList(
          itemCount: itemCount,
          itemBuilder: (BuildContext context, int index) {
            return Card(
              margin: EdgeInsets.all(margin), // Give a margin so the elements are visible in the golden images.
              key: ValueKey<int>(items[index]),
              child: SizedBox(
                height: height - 2 * margin,
                child: ReorderableDragStartListener(
                  index: index,
                  child: Text('item ${items[index]} ' + ('#' * (index + 1))),
                ),
              ),
            );
          },
          onReorder: handleReorder,
        ),
      ),
    );

    // The list has six elements of height 50.
    await tester.pumpWidget(widget);

    await expectLater(find.byWidget(widget), matchesGoldenFile('0.png')); // Display the initial list.

    // Start gesture on the second item
    final TestGesture drag = await tester.startGesture(tester.getCenter(find.textContaining('item 1')));
    await tester.pump(kPressTimeout);

    // Drag enough to move down the 2nd item after the 4th one.
    await drag.moveTo(
      tester.getCenter(find.byKey(const ValueKey(3))) + const Offset(0.0, height / 2) + const Offset(0.0, extra),
    );
    await tester.pump();
    await expectLater(find.byWidget(widget), matchesGoldenFile('1.png')); // Displays where is the dragged element is before the drop.
    await tester.pumpAndSettle();
    await expectLater(find.byWidget(widget), matchesGoldenFile('2.png')); // Displays how the list is moving before the drop.

    await drag.up();
    await tester.pumpAndSettle();

    expect(items, orderedEquals(<int>[0, 2, 3, 1, 4, 5])); // The 2nd element (index 1) should have been dropped after the 4th element (index 3).
  });
}
```

Title_Description:
Wrong help message in `flutter gen-l10n` ## Steps to Reproduce

1. Run `flutter gen-l10n --help`.
2. See the help of `--[no-]nullable-getter`.

**Expected results:** <!-- what did you want to see? -->

"If this value is set to false"

**Actual results:** <!-- what did you see? -->

"If this value is set to true"

> If this value is set to true,
> then a null check is performed on the returned value of
> Localizations.of(context), removing the need for null
> checking in user code.

## Additional context

A PR (#90180) by someone else to fix this has been closed without being merged because of a missing test.

I gave up fixing it myself, not knowing what test was needed, but I thought I should at least file an issue about it so that it'd catch someone's eye.

A text with line breaks

**Actual results:**
A text without line breaks and triggers a press on ListTile.

      title: 'Flutter Demo',
      theme: ThemeData(
        primarySwatch: Colors.blue,
      ),
      home: const MyHomePage(title: 'Flutter Demo Home Page'),

Title_Description:
[Pointer interceptor] Mouse events are propogated through the drawer <!-- Thank you for using Flutter!

     If you are looking for support, please check out our documentation
     or consider asking a question on Stack Overflow:
      * https://flutter.dev/
      * https://api.flutter.dev/
      * https://stackoverflow.com/questions/tagged/flutter?sort=frequent

     If you have found a bug or if our documentation doesn't have an answer
     to what you're looking for, then fill out the template below. Please read
     our guide to filing a bug first: https://flutter.dev/docs/resources/bug-reports
-->

## Steps to Reproduce

<!-- Please include full steps to reproduce so that we can reproduce the problem. -->

1. Create a `web` project, add the following lines to the `pubspec.yaml` dependencies: `html_editor_enhanced: ^2.4.0+1` and `pointer_interceptor: ^0.9.3`
2.  Execute `flutter run` on the code sample <!-- (see "Code sample" section below) -->
2. Open the drawer, then click on the  `ListTile` elements to see that the ones that overlaps with the editor can't be interacted with
3. Tap the FAB to make the editor disappear, then open the drawer and check that the red debug overlay is visible (and thus all the `ListTile` elements are working as expected)

**Expected results:** The click should be intercepted by the `PointerInterceptor` elements, not by the underlying HTML editor. Moreover, the red debug layer should be always visible, despite having an `HTMLElementView` in the widget tree. The fact that the debug layer is not there might help understand what's happening.

**Actual results:** All the interactions with widgets that overlap with the HTML editor are intercepted by it. Also, the red debug layer appears only if there is no `HTMLElementView` visible.

<details>
<summary>Code sample</summary>

<!--
      Please create a minimal reproducible sample that shows the problem
      and attach it below between the lines with the backticks.

      To create it you can use `flutter create bug` command and update the `main.dart` file.

      Alternatively, you can use https://dartpad.dev/
      which is capable of creating and running small Flutter apps.

      Without this we will unlikely be able to progress on the issue, and because of that
      we regretfully will have to close it.
-->

```dart
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';
import 'package:html_editor_enhanced/html_editor.dart';
import 'package:pointer_interceptor/pointer_interceptor.dart';

void main() {
  runApp(const MyApp());
}

class MyApp extends StatelessWidget {
  const MyApp({Key? key}) : super(key: key);

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return const MaterialApp(
      title: 'Flutter Demo',
      home: MyHomePage(title: 'Flutter Demo Home Page'),
    );
  }
}

class MyHomePage extends StatefulWidget {
  const MyHomePage({Key? key, required this.title}) : super(key: key);
  final String title;

  @override
  State<MyHomePage> createState() => _MyHomePageState();
}

class _MyHomePageState extends State<MyHomePage> {
  var htmlEC = HtmlEditorController();
  var showEditor = true;

  final lorem = "Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet.";
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Scaffold(
      appBar: AppBar(title: Text(widget.title)),
      drawer: PointerInterceptor(
          debug: true,
          child: Drawer(
            child: ListView(
              children: [
                ListTile(onTap: () => _onTap(1), title: const Text("List tile 1")),
                ListTile(onTap: () => _onTap(2), title: const Text("List tile 2")),
                ListTile(onTap: () => _onTap(3), title: const Text("List tile 3")),
                ListTile(onTap: () => _onTap(4), title: const Text("List tile 4")),
                ListTile(onTap: () => _onTap(5), title: const Text("List tile 5")),
              ],
            ),
          )),
      body: showEditor
          ? HtmlEditor(
              controller: htmlEC, //required
              htmlEditorOptions: HtmlEditorOptions(
                initialText: lorem,
              ),
              otherOptions: const OtherOptions(
                height: 650,
              ),
            )
          : const Text("Editor hidden"),
      floatingActionButton: FloatingActionButton(
        onPressed: () => setState(() => showEditor = !showEditor),
        tooltip: 'Increment',
        child: const Icon(Icons.add),
      ),
    );
  }

  void _onTap(int i) {
    ScaffoldMessenger.of(context).showSnackBar(SnackBar(content: Text("Tapped list tile #$i")));
  }
}


```

</details>

Framework's matchesGoldenFile should assert that file name has right structure https://github.com/flutter/flutter/pull/98772 broke the tree because the file name provided to matchesGoldenFile was missing `.png`. We should assert that file names have the right structure - maybe even that they are unique at least for the given file?

incorrect:
```dart
matchesGoldenFile('slider_start_text_scale_1_width_0'),
```

correct:
```dart
matchesGoldenFile('slider_start_text_scale_1_width_0.png'),
```

Title_Description: When moved from staging -> prod (bringup = false) the first run shown in the dashboard uses the staging build number instead of the prod build number `Mac module_test_ios` was marked flaky, and was running in staging with build numbers 629 ,630, [631](https://ci.chromium.org/p/flutter/builders/staging/Mac%20module_test_ios/631)... It was marked unflaky and moved back to prod in https://github.com/flutter/flutter/pull/99009. The first time it ran in prod in the dashboard it correctly shows links to `prod` but incorrectly lists the n+1 staging build number, instead of the prod build number. The first build listed is incorrectly [prod 632](https://ci.chromium.org/p/flutter/builders/prod/Mac%20module_test_ios/632), which is ancient (and happened to fail), and the next is correctly [prod 5245](https://ci.chromium.org/p/flutter/builders/prod/Mac%20module_test_ios/5245). This made me start investigating why this test was "flaky" again when it really wasn't.

Title_Description:
Log links do not work for LUCI windows bots e.g. on https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/flutter/builders/staging/Windows%20windows_home_scroll_perf__timeline_summary/43/overview, clicking any of the log links leads to an error page. It looks like it's trying to mix Windows and Unix style path separators...?

@CaseyHillers @keyonghan @godofredoc fyi
Labels: team: infra;P4
Creator: dnfield

Title_Description:
[Android]Semantics on TextField is not updated when changing obscureText to false Given a `TextField` widget, if `obscureText` is initialy to `true`, and then changed to `false`, semantics is not properly updated: TalkBack still reads "bullets" instead of the input characters.

## Steps to Reproduce

1. Execute `flutter run` on the code sample 
2. Enter "hello" in the text field
3. Tap the "Disable obscure" button
4. Activate TalkBack
5. Select the text field

**Expected results:**
TalkBack says: "hello"

**Actual results:**
TalkBack says: "5 bullets"
<details>
<summary>Code sample</summary>

```dart
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';

void main() {
  runApp(const ObscureApp());
}

class ObscureApp extends StatelessWidget {
  const ObscureApp({Key? key}) : super(key: key);

  // This widget is the root of your application.
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return MaterialApp(
      title: 'Obscure semantics bug',
      theme: ThemeData(
        primarySwatch: Colors.blue,
      ),
      home: HomePage(),
    );
  }
}

class HomePage extends StatefulWidget {
  HomePage({Key? key}) : super(key: key);

  @override
  _HomePageState createState() => _HomePageState();
}

class _HomePageState extends State<HomePage> {
  bool _obscureText = true;

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Scaffold(
      body: Padding(
        padding: const EdgeInsets.all(16.0),
        child: Column(
          mainAxisAlignment: MainAxisAlignment.center,
          children: [
            TextField(obscureText: _obscureText),
            ElevatedButton(
              onPressed: () async {
                setState(() {
                  _obscureText = false;
                });
              },
              child: Text('Disable obscure'),
            ),
            ElevatedButton(
              onPressed: () async {
                setState(() {
                  _obscureText = true;
                });
              },
              child: Text('Enable obscure'),
            )
          ],
        ),
      ),
    );
  }
}

```

</details>

Title_Description:
[auto_submit] Rebase outdated pull requests to tip of tree Other auto submit bots offer something similar. It would be useful if a pull request was behind the tip of tree by N commits that the bot tried to rebase it. If it ran into issues, it leaves a comments and removes the auto submit label.

I think N=5 would be a good start.
Labels: new feature;team: infra;P4
Creator: CaseyHillers

Title_Description:
[cocoon] Create request handler returns latest green commits The goal is someone can make an HTTP request to `/api/public/get-green-commits?repo=$repo`, and receive a list of the commit shas that had green runs.

A green commit is used to help the release tooling find commits Flutter infrastructure has validated. The rules are:
1. A commit had all its tests run (at least those that are not in bringup)
2. All those blocking tasks were green

This is similar to `/api/public/get-status`, with the added logic above.
Labels: team: infra;P4
Creator: CaseyHillers

Title_Description:
[dashboard] Make it easy to swap repos We should move the repo dropdown from the settings dialog into the `AppBar` directly.

This will make it easier for developers to swap between repos instead of needing to open a new tab

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/2148558/157774968-8aa6d564-12e5-4db2-9b18-c39a584c7319.png)
Labels: team: infra;P4
Creator: CaseyHillers
